<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">I. <UNDER>INTRODUCTION</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. These written submissions are filed in respect of an application for advice and direction brought by MNP Ltd. (the &ldquo;Trustee&rdquo;), in its capacity as Trustee of the bankrupt estate of Cindy Hannele Chomistek (&ldquo;Ms. Chomistek&rdquo; or the &ldquo;bankrupt&rdquo;), as to entitlement to certain income tax refunds paid as a result of disability tax credits claimed by Ms. Chomistek on behalf of her disabled child.</P>
<P>2. Due to amendments made to the relevant provisions of the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM> (Canada) (the &ldquo;BIA&rdquo;) over the years and divergent court decisions across Canada, Registrar Prowse directed the Trustee's application for advice and direction be adjourned to be heard as a special application.</P>
<P>3. Neither the bankrupt estate nor Ms. Chomistek had the resources to engage legal counsel. However, Registrar Prowse considered it necessary and appropriate that the legal issues raised in this matter be researched and briefed by an impartial legal advisor for the assistance of this Honourable Court. Accordingly, he appointed Miles Davison LLP as <EM>amicus curiae</EM> to prepare and make submissions at this special application. In these submissions, documents attached to Part 1 (Analysis) will be tabbed alphabetically, while cases and commentary attached to Part 2 (Authorities) will be tabbed numerically. A filed copy of the Order granted by Registrar Prowse on October 3<SUP>rd</SUP>, 2017 appointing the <EM>Amicus Curiae</EM> is attached at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB A</BOLD>.</P>
<P>4. We have also served the Office of the Superintendent of Bankruptcy (&ldquo;OSB&rdquo;) with notice of this special application by our letter dated October 26<SUP>th</SUP>, 2017, a copy of which (without enclosures) is attached at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB B.</BOLD></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">II. <UNDER>MATERIALS FILED</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. In addition to its application for advice and direction, the Trustee filed a Trustee's Report dated July 14<SUP>th</SUP>, 2017. The bankrupt filed written submissions in response dated July 30<SUP>th</SUP>, 2017.</P>
<P>6. No Affidavits have been filed and no examinations have occurred. However, the basic facts are not in dispute.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">III. <UNDER>RELEVANT FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>7. Ms. Chomistek assigned herself into bankruptcy on May 14<SUP>th</SUP>, 2013, after her consumer proposal was not accepted. MNP Ltd. was appointed as Trustee of her bankrupt estate. Ms. Chomistek has not previously been bankrupt.</P>
<P>8. A copy of Ms. Chomistek's Statement of Affairs as a bankrupt is attached as Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo; to the Trustee's Report and is attached here at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB C</BOLD>.</P>
<P>9. The Trustee's Final Statement of Receipts and Disbursements is attached as Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo; to the Trustee's Report and is attached here at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB D</BOLD>. Ms. Chomistek had proven unsecured claims of $109,947.50 and her creditors received very small dividends.</P>
<P>10. Ms. Chomistek was automatically discharged from bankruptcy on February 15<SUP>th</SUP>, 2014. The Trustee received its own discharge on September 29<SUP>th</SUP>, 2015. A current OSB search of Ms. Chomistek is attached at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB E</BOLD>.</P>
<P>11. After Ms. Chomistek was discharged from bankruptcy, she came across a newspaper advertisement regarding disability tax credits. Ms. Chomistek states in her submissions that, after further inquiry, she realized she could apply for a disability tax credit on behalf of her disabled child for the current taxation year and previous taxation years, going back to the time her child was 4 years old. Ms. Chomistek accordingly claimed these credits and re-filed her personal income tax returns for the years 2004 through 2014 with Canada Revenue Agency (&ldquo;CRA&rdquo;).</P>
<P>12. On January 8<SUP>th</SUP>, 2016, CRA sent a letter to Ms. Chomistek discussing her request for an adjustment to her personal income tax returns to &ldquo;include the transfer of your [child's] disability amount for the 2005 to 2014 taxation years&rdquo;. A copy of this letter is attached as Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo; to the Trustee's Report and is attached here at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB F</BOLD>.</P>
<P>13. The Trustee subsequently received two cheques from CRA totalling $20,339.82. According to the Trustee's Report, these cheques were made payable to MNP Ltd. in its capacity as Trustee of Ms. Chomistek's bankrupt estate. As well, the Trustee received Notices of Reassessment pertaining to these tax refunds. The taxation years involved and the refunds received for each year are summarized in the Trustee's Report (page 2) and re-stated here:
