<P>14. These funds are currently being held by MNP Ltd. in its general trust account. These are the funds at issue in this application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">IV. <UNDER>LEGISLATION</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM> (Canada) (&ldquo;BIA&rdquo;)</UNDER></TI>
<P>15. <UNDER>Section 2</UNDER>
<P1>Section 2 of the BIA broadly defines &ldquo;property&rdquo; as follows:
<QUOTE><P>property means any type of property, whether situated in Canada or elsewhere, and includes money, goods, things in action, land and every description of property, whether real or personal, legal or equitable, as well as obligations, easements and every description of estate, interest and profit, present or future, vested or contingent, in, arising out of or incident to property;</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>We note that Section 2 does not define &ldquo;income&rdquo; or &ldquo;revenue&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>16. <UNDER>Section 67</UNDER>
<P1>Section 67 of the BIA describes the &ldquo;property&rdquo; of a bankrupt divisible among his or her creditors. In our respectful submission, it is critical to an understanding and analysis of the issues in this application to appreciate the legislative history of section 67 and, in particular, the substantial amendments which came into force in 2008 and 2009, which we discuss below. We attach the following to Part 1:
