<P>18. In 2005, a comprehensive insolvency reform package was introduced in Parliament to modernize the BIA and the <EM>Companies' Creditors Arrangement Act</EM> (&ldquo;CCAA&rdquo;), as well as to create the legislative framework for the Wage Earner Protection Program. The Bill received Royal assent on November 25<SUP>th</SUP>, 2005, thereby becoming Chapter 47 of the <EM>Statutes of Canada</EM>, 2005 (&ldquo;Chapter 47&rdquo;). The pages of Chapter 47 relevant to this application are attached at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB M</BOLD>.</P>
<P>19. Certain technical amendments were required to be made to Chapter 47 before some of its provisions could be brought into force. These technical amendments were contained in a Bill to amend the BIA, the CCAA, the <EM>Wage Earner Protection Program Act</EM> (&ldquo;WEPPA&rdquo;) and Chapter 47. This Bill received Royal assent on December 14<SUP>th</SUP>, 2007, thereby becoming Chapter 36 of the <EM>Statutes of Canada</EM>, 2007 (&ldquo;Chapter 36&rdquo;). The pages of Chapter 36 relevant to this application are attached at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB N</BOLD>.</P>
<P>20. Certain provisions of Chapter 47 were only to come into force on proclamation, including the amendments to sections 67 and 68. Some of these provisions in Chapter 47, as amended by Chapter 36, came into force on July 7<SUP>th</SUP>, 2008 by means of SI 2008-78, which is attached at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB O</BOLD>. The rest of these provisions of Chapter 47, as amended by Chapter 36, came into force on September 18<SUP>th</SUP>, 2009, pursuant to SI 2009-68, which is attached at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB P</BOLD>.</P>
<P>21. As a consequence of these amendments and later proclamations, the amendments to section 67 came into force on July 7<SUP>th</SUP>, 2008 and the amendments to section 68 came into force on September 18<SUP>th</SUP>, 2009. What is confusing is that the amendments to sections 67 and 68 of the BIA introduced by Chapter 47 were not immediately proclaimed in force, but the further revisions to these amendments made by Chapter 36 received Royal assent on December 14<SUP>th</SUP>, 2007, so it was section 57 of Chapter 47, as already amended by section 32 of Chapter 36, which came into force on July 7<SUP>th</SUP>, 2008 and amended section 67 to read as it does today. Similarly, section 58 of Chapter 47, as already amended by section 33 of Chapter 36, came into force on September 18<SUP>th</SUP>, 2009 and amended section 68 to read as it does today.</P>
<P>22. Section 71 of the BIA is the general vesting section and it reads as follows:
<QUOTE><P>On a bankruptcy order being made or an assignment being filed with an official receiver, a bankrupt ceases to have any capacity to dispose of or otherwise deal with their property, which shall, subject to this Act and to the rights of secured creditors, immediately pass to and vest in the trustee named in the bankruptcy order or assignment, and in any case of change of trustee the property shall pass from trustee to trustee without any assignment or transfer.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER><EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (Canada) (&ldquo;ITA&rdquo;)</UNDER></TI>
<P>23. Section 118.3 of the ITA sets out the provisions governing disability tax credits and is attached at <BOLD>Part 1, TAB Q.</BOLD></P>
<P>24. Generally speaking, the disability tax credit (sometimes referred to as a &ldquo;DTC&rdquo;) is a non-refundable tax credit available to disabled taxpayers, or taxpayers upon whom disabled individuals are financially dependent and/or for whom they provide care, provided they meet the conditions set out in section 118.3 of the ITA. On its website, Canada Revenue Agency describes the purpose of the DTC as &ldquo;to provide for greater tax equity by allowing some relief for disability costs, since these are unavoidable additional expenses that other taxpayers don't have to face&rdquo;. We will further discuss the nature and character of a DTC and the tax refund it can generate below.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">V. <UNDER>ISSUES</UNDER></TI>
<P>25. The issue is who, as between the Trustee and Ms. Chomistek, is entitled to all or part of the income tax refunds received by the Trustee as a result of disability tax credits claimed by Ms. Chomistek, after the date of her discharge from bankruptcy, on behalf of her disabled child.</P>
<P>26. The answer to this question will depend on the nature of a DTC and the true character of the income tax refunds it generates. Therefore, to answer this main question, we must consider these further issues:
<P1>(a) Are the tax refunds payable by reason of the disability tax credits claimed by Ms. Chomistek &ldquo;property&rdquo; or &ldquo;income&rdquo;, and can they, for some purposes, be both?</P1>
<P1>(b) If such refunds are &ldquo;property&rdquo;, then are they property of the bankrupt at the date of bankruptcy or acquired by or devolving on her before her discharge or, put another way, given that the tax refunds were applied for and paid after the date of Ms. Chomistek's discharge, do we look at the time of receipt or the taxation years to which the refunds relate?</P1>
<P1>(c) Are the tax refunds monies to be held in trust by Ms. Chomistek for her disabled child or, put another way, whose property is it?</P1>
<P1>(d) Are the tax refunds &ldquo;exempt from execution or seizure&rdquo; under the laws of Alberta [section 67(1)(b)] or &ldquo;otherwise not subject to the operation of this Act&rdquo; [section 67(1)(c)(i)]?</P1>
<P1>(e) Are the tax refunds to be treated differently depending on the period to which they relate, that is, prior to bankruptcy, the year in which bankruptcy occurred, between bankruptcy and discharge, or after discharge?</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">VI. <UNDER>ANALYSIS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>What is the nature of a disability tax credit?</UNDER></TI>
<P>27. There is a good discussion of the nature of a disability tax credit by Registrar Diamond in <CASEREF><SOC>Re Bowerbank-Buckley</SOC></CASEREF> (to be further discussed below). At paragraph 25 of his reasons, Registrar Diamond quotes Professor David Duff as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Professor David Duff explains in McGill Law Journal article <UNDER>Disability and the Income Tax</UNDER>, that a DTC is ultimately intended to be a compensation for expenses, but has been drafted in the form of a fixed credit so that it can cover generalized, non-itemizable costs associated with living with a disability:</P>
<P>.... to the extent that disabilities impose various kinds of costs, some of which are indirect and difficult to itemize, these are appropriately recognized through a credit or deduction equal to a fixed dollar amount. ... Likewise, to the extent that restricted access to the marketplace and society at large causes disabled persons to incur higher costs for basic goods and services like groceries, a fixed credit or deduction recognizes these additional costs. In this respect, the DTC can be likened to an additional personal exemption to recognize non-discretionary but difficult to itemize costs associated with a mental or physical disability .....</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>28. Registrar Diamond goes on to say, at paragraph 26:
<QUOTE><P>This interpretation is significant, in light of the weight that Romilly, J. [in <EM>Bolz</EM>] placed upon the status of the funds as coming from non-refundable fixed credit status of the DTC. The DTC, in its intent, is related to taxable income in the same way that expense deductions would be: it is simply being framed in the form of a fixed credit to address the difficulty in accounting for many of the expenses associated with various disabilities. In that regard, <UNDER>the money is in the nature of a refund of the taxpayer's money</UNDER>, and not a grant of funds from the government's coffers. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Case Review</UNDER></TI>
<P>29. There is no way to draw any consistent conclusion from the reported cases which have considered the issues surrounding disability tax credits and the income tax refunds they generate. The dollar amounts involved are often relatively small and the trustee and/or the bankrupt frequently do not have legal counsel. As a result, not all of the relevant factors and considerations which, in our respectful view, should have been considered by some of the various courts were considered and, simply put, we think a number of the reported decisions are incorrect.</P>
<P>30. However, as <EM>amicus curiae</EM>, we think it is important to review all of the most frequently reported decisions, with a view to the timing of the decisions and the particular versions of sections 67 and 68 then being considered. Accordingly, we propose to review the decided cases in more or less chronological order, except that we will begin with the decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Marzetti v. Marzetti</SOC></CASEREF> and the Ontario Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Re Landry</SOC></CASEREF>, as these 2 decisions are critical to the analysis.</P>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Marzetti</EM> (1994)</UNDER></TI>
<P>31. In <CASEREF><SOC>Marzetti v. Marzetti</SOC><CITE>[1994] 2 SCR 765</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 1,</BOLD> the issue was entitlement to an income tax refund payable to the bankrupt which pertained to income he earned <UNDER>after</UNDER> his assignment into bankruptcy. The portions of the decision which are relevant here are the Court's discussion of whether the income tax refund is &ldquo;income&rdquo; or &ldquo;property&rdquo;, beginning at paragraph 32 of the decision.</P>
<P>32. At the time <EM>Marzetti</EM> was decided, section 67(1)(c) of the BIA simply read: &ldquo;all property wherever situated of the bankrupt at the date of his bankruptcy or that may be acquired by or devolve on him before his discharge&rdquo; (see Part 1, TAB G). It did not include the phrase &ldquo;including any refund owing to the bankrupt under the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> in respect of the calendar year&mdash;or the fiscal year of the bankrupt if it is different from the calendar year&mdash;<UNDER>in which the bankrupt became bankrupt</UNDER>&rdquo; (emphasis added), nor did it include the exceptions in paragraphs 67(1)(c) (i) and (ii), the more relevant of which is (i) &ldquo;[the portion that] is not subject to the operation of this Act&rdquo;. [We note, in passing, that the current version of section 67(1)(c) only references any refund owing to the bankrupt under the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> in respect of the year in which the bankrupt became bankrupt. It is does <UNDER>not</UNDER> expressly include or refer to income tax refunds for years <UNDER>prior to</UNDER> the date of bankruptcy, although some commentators and some of the newer cases have read that into the language.]</P>
<P>33. Similarly, the version of section 68 of the BIA which the Court considered in <EM>Marzetti</EM> (see Part 1, TAB J) included the phrase &ldquo;notwithstanding section 67&rdquo;, while the current version of section 68 (see Part 1, TAB L) says &ldquo;despite paragraph 67(1)(b) and (b.3)&rdquo;. Most importantly, the version of section 68 considered in <EM>Marzetti</EM> did not limit &ldquo;total income&rdquo; to a bankrupt's revenues of &ldquo;whatever nature or from whatever source that are <UNDER>earned</UNDER> or <UNDER>received</UNDER> by the bankrupt <UNDER>between the date of the bankruptcy and the date of the bankrupt's discharge</UNDER>&rdquo; (emphasis added). The version of section 68 in <EM>Marzetti</EM> instead dealt with language which read, &ldquo;where a bankrupt is in receipt of, or is entitled to receive, any salary, wages or other remuneration from any person employing, or using the services of, the bankrupt&rdquo;, without any time limitation.</P>
<P>34. However, notwithstanding the amendments to sections 67 and 68 of the BIA which have been enacted since <EM>Marzetti</EM> was decided, this case is still very instructive and contains many concepts still directly applicable to the issues in this application.</P>
<P>35. Mr. Justice Iacobucci began his analysis by considering whether, in general terms, what was then the <EM>Bankruptcy Act</EM>'s reference to &ldquo;property&rdquo; was broad enough to embrace the facts of the case before him. He noted that Marzetti's income tax return was not filed until after his discharge from bankruptcy, and the refund related to income he earned following his assignment into bankruptcy. Accordingly, at the &ldquo;date of his bankruptcy&rdquo;, Marzetti had no interest in the tax refund because he had not earned the income yet. Nevertheless, His Lordship considered whether there was still a proprietary character to tax overpayments, noting that, not surprisingly, the Act defined the word &ldquo;property&rdquo; in very broad terms. He found that even if a taxpayer who makes overpayments has no right to compel a refund prior to filing a return, that taxpayer has at least a future and contingent interest in the ultimate tax refund (paragraph 38). He concluded that the Act's reference to &ldquo;property&rdquo; was broad enough to embrace the facts of the case. More specifically, he concluded that Marzetti &ldquo;acquired at least a future and contingent interest in his income tax refund at the time excess overpayments were withheld on his behalf (paragraph 40).</P>
<P>36. Mr. Justice Iacobucci then turned to a consideration of whether what were then sections 67(c) and (d) should be read conjunctively or disjunctively. He found that the word &ldquo;and&rdquo; which appears at the end of 67(c) must, by reason of its context, be read disjunctively (paragraph 45). In the result, he concluded that a bankrupt's interest in a post-bankruptcy income tax refund can be considered &ldquo;property&rdquo; for the purposes of section 67(c), and section 67(d) in no way qualified the operation of section 67(c).</P>
<P>37. However, his analysis did not end there. He found that his initial conclusion that the refund was &ldquo;property&rdquo; was overruled by section 68.</P>
<P>38. Mr. Justice Iacobucci's discussion of whether section 68 was a &ldquo;complete code&rdquo; in respect of a bankrupt's wages, or not, contains concepts which are directly applicable to the facts of this case. In paragraph 51, he discussed the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Industrial Acceptance Corp. v. Lalonde</SOC><CITE>[1952] 2 SCR 109</CITE></CASEREF>. In that case, the court was asked to decide whether wages or salary could be excluded from the definition of divisible property by what later became section 67(b) of the <EM>Bankruptcy Act</EM> [now section 67(1)(b) of the BIA], Section 67(b) then provided that divisible property would not comprise &ldquo;any property that as against the bankrupt is exempt from execution or seizure under the laws of the province within which the property is situated ...&rdquo;. The argument was made that this language did not exclude wages or salary because wages or salary could only be reached by a garnishee or attachment procedure, and not &ldquo;execution or seizure&rdquo;. The Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Industrial Acceptance Corp.</EM> rejected this distinction and held, at page 117, as quoted by Mr. Justice Iacobucci at paragraph 51 of his decision in <EM>Marzetti</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>It would appear that Parliament in adopting the language of [section 67(b)] intended that only such portion of the salary as was subject to seizure by legal process under the law of the respective provinces should vest in the trustee. Moreover, the omission of any such provision as that contained in section 51(1) of the <EM>English Act</EM>, under which, on the application of the trustee, an order might be made against the bankrupt in receipt of a salary to pay the whole or part thereof to the trustee, appears to support the foregoing view.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>39. In other words, as Mr. Justice Iacobucci put it at paragraphs 51 and 52:
<QUOTE><P>In modern terms, <EM>Industrial Acceptance Corp.</EM> established that the language of section 67(b), which removes from &ldquo;property of a bankrupt divisible among his creditors ... any property that as against the bankrupt is exempt from execution or seizure under the laws of the province&rdquo;, can operate to exclude wages or salary as contemplated by provincial exemptions.</P>
<P>In effect, therefore, the pre-amendment position was this: after taking into account provincial wage and salary exemptions, any remaining wages or salary of a bankrupt was &ldquo;property of a bankrupt divisible among his creditors&rdquo;. These excess wages vested automatically in the trustee.&rdquo;</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>40. Mr. Justice Iacobucci went on to find that section 68 was a substantive provision which, because it applied &ldquo;notwithstanding section 67&rdquo;, operated as a complete code in respect of the listed forms of property (paragraph 61). Furthermore, while there have been attempts in some subsequently decided cases to limit Mr. Justice Iacobucci's reasoning to only post-bankruptcy wages, our respectful view is that his reasoning was intended to apply to both pre-bankruptcy and post-bankruptcy wages, that is, wages owing to the bankrupt at the date of bankruptcy and wages earned by the bankrupt prior to his or her discharge. However, given the last amendments to section 68 which now restrict &ldquo;total income&rdquo; to revenues earned or received during the period of the bankruptcy, we think there are good arguments to be made that the &ldquo;pre-amendment position&rdquo; described in <EM>Marzetti</EM> now exists with respect to pre-bankruptcy wages that are not received during bankruptcy.</P>
<P>41. Finally, having concluded that anything called &ldquo;wages&rdquo; will not vest automatically in a trustee, because of how sections 67 and 68, as they then read, fit together, His Lordship turned to the question of whether the income tax refund should be considered &ldquo;wages&rdquo; for the purposes of section 68.</P>
<P>42. In the Alberta Court of Appeal's decision in <EM>Marzetti</EM>, Mr. Justice Major held that Marzetti's refund retained the character of wages to the extent that it represented a return of employer-withholding deductions. Mr. Justice Iacobucci agreed with this conclusion but, in our respectful view, he went somewhat further. At paragraphs 78 and 79 of his decision, he said this:
<QUOTE><P>In my opinion, the transformation of Marzetti's wages over time does not alter their fundamental character. Marzetti earned a certain amount as wages after his voluntary assignment into bankruptcy. The fact that some portion of his wages was, by virtue of statute, automatically directed toward his tax liability does not affect the question. <UNDER>The intervention of statute speaks to how Marzetti spent his wages, not to how much he earned in the first place</UNDER>. In common parlance, taxpayers do not draw false distinctions between the wages they earn and the refunds they receive. As stated by Fullagar, J. in <EM>Federal Commissioner of Taxation</EM> supra, &ldquo;his right to payment arises because, and only because, he worked for a remuneration which is found, on a contingency which was contemplated throughout, not to have been paid to him in full.&rdquo; (p. 322)</P>
<P>Therefore, Major, J.A. was, I suggest, entirely justified in concluding that a tax refund is analytically similar to deferred wages in this case. He noted that &ldquo;if there is any money that can be easily traced in a modern society, it is the amount of taxes paid and the amount of taxes owed&rdquo; (p. 133). It is difficult to dispute this statement and I reject the ... suggestion that a wages-characterization is precluded by the commingling of withheld sums in the Consolidated Revenue Fund. Equally, I agree with Major, J.A. that there is no necessary inconsistency between holding that at tax refund is a debt owed by the Crown, and holding that a tax refund represents deferred wages originally owed by an employer.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>43. Mr. Justice Iacobucci also agreed with Mr. Justice Major there was no doubt in the case before him that the post-bankruptcy income tax refund derived from Marzetti's wages, but he noted, &ldquo;(O)f course tax refunds can be generated from other sources of income. In the words of Major, J.A., therefore, the wages characterization &lsquo;depends on the nature of the refund&rsquo;&rdquo; (paragraph 80). In all of the circumstances, Mr. Justice Iacobucci concluded that the income tax refund payable to Marzetti &ldquo;retained&rdquo; its character as &ldquo;wages&rdquo; and that section 68, which governed as a complete code for wages, applied.</P>
<P>44. Similarly, in our case, there is no suggestion that Ms. Chomistek's income derived from anything other than her employment or other work.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Landry</EM> (2000)</UNDER></TI>
<P>45. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Landry</SOC><YEAR>2000</YEAR><CITE>21 CBR (4th) 58</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 2</BOLD>, was a decision of the Ontario Court of Appeal. In that case, Ms. Landry had been dismissed from her employment as a pilot prior to making an assignment into bankruptcy in 1997. She brought a claim for unjust dismissal. She was discharged from bankruptcy in October, 1998, although the trustee had not yet been discharged at the time of the hearing before the Ontario Court of Appeal. In December, 1998, after Ms. Landry was discharged from bankruptcy, an arbitrator found she had been unjustly dismissed. While the exact amount to be paid to her was uncertain, the parties agreed that, as part of the award, some monies for lost wages would be paid.</P>
<P>46. By the time the <EM>Landry</EM> case came before the court, sections 67 and 68 had been amended. The versions of section 67 and 68 considered by the Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Landry</EM> appear at Part 1, TAB H and TAB K. The amendments made to section 67 since <EM>Marzetti</EM> were not particularly germane here, as those amendments simply added section 67(1)(b.1), dealing with goods and service tax credit payments. However, the amendments to section 68 were more substantial and, by the time <EM>Landry</EM> was decided, section 68 contained a definition of &ldquo;total income&rdquo; which was defined to include &ldquo;notwithstanding paragraph 67(1)(b) and (b.1), all revenues of a bankrupt of whatever nature or source&rdquo;. Again, we note at this time &ldquo;total income&rdquo; was not limited to amounts earned or received during the bankruptcy.</P>
<P>47. Mr. Justice Charron began his analysis in <EM>Landry</EM> by considering whether Ms. Landry's claim against the airline or any part of the resulting award constituted &ldquo;property&rdquo; that vested in the trustee under sections 67 and 71(2) of the BIA. At paragraph 15 of his decision, he said:
<QUOTE><P>It is clear that s. 67(1)(c) is wide enough to encompass Landry's claim against her former employer and, consequently, any award of damages (other than those relating to personal claims, see footnote 1, <EM>supra</EM>) would form part of the property divisible among her creditors under that provision. A question then arises whether any part of the property falls within the exception made for exempt property under section 67(1)(b).</P></QUOTE>
We note that in footnote 1, the trustee acknowledged that any award of damages relating to personal claims other than for lost wages would not form part of the bankrupt's estate, on the authority of <CASEREF><SOC>Holley v. Gifford Smith Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, a case which we discuss in more detail below.</P>
<P>48. Mr. Justice Charron then went on to consider whether any provincial exemption applied to a lost wages award pursuant to section 67(1)(b) so as to except any part of the property from the estate of the bankrupt. Ms. Landry relied on provisions of the Ontario <EM>Wages Act</EM> which provided that 80% of a person's wages were exempt from seizure or garnishment.</P>
<P>49. Mr. Justice Charron discussed the decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Wallace v. United Grain Growers Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1997] 3 SCR 701</CITE></CASEREF>. In <EM>Wallace</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada held that an arbitrator's award of damages for unjust dismissal, insofar as it related to lost wages, can be equated to actual wages. We have not attached a complete copy of the <EM>Wallace</EM> decision to our authorities. However, the headnote and the relevant pages from <EM>Wallace</EM> are attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 3</BOLD>.</P>
<P>50. The finding in <EM>Wallace</EM> that is of relevance to this application, and of relevance to the analysis in <EM>Landry</EM>, was the finding by the Supreme Court of Canada that Wallace, an undischarged bankrupt, could maintain his action against his former employer for damages for wrongful dismissal not because of the timing of the acquisition of the property but rather because of the nature of the property in question, which the court equated to &ldquo;wages&rdquo;. At paragraph 20, the Ontario Court of Appeal quoted Mr. Justice Iacobucci in <EM>Wallace</EM>, who said the following:
<QUOTE><P>As I see the matter, the underlying nature of the damages awarded in a wrongful dismissal action is clearly akin to the &ldquo;wages&rdquo; referred to in s. 68(1). In the absence of just cause, an employer remains free to dismiss an employee at an y time provided that reasonable notice of the termination is given. In providing the employee with reasonable notice, the employer has two options: either to require the employee to continue working for the duration of that period or to give the employee pay in lieu of notice: D. Harris, <EM>Wrongful Dismissal</EM> (1989) (loose-leaf), at p. 3&ndash;10. There can be no doubt that if the employer opted to require the employee to continue working during the notice period, his or her earnings during this time would constitute wages or salary under s. 68(1) of the Act. <UNDER>The only difference between these earnings and pay in lieu of notice is that the employee receives a lump sum payment instead of having that sum spread out over the course of the notice period. The nature of those funds remains the same and thus s. 68(1) will also apply in these circumstances.</UNDER></P>
<P>In the event that an employee is wrongfully dismissed, the measure of damages for wrongful dismissal is the salary the employee would have earned had the employee worked during the period of notice to which he or she was entitled. <CASEREF><SOC>Sylvester v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>[1997] 2 S.C.R. 315</CITE></CASEREF>. The fact that this sum is awarded as damages at trial in no way alters <UNDER>the fundamental character of the money</UNDER>. An award of damages in a wrongful dismissal action is in reality the wages that the employer ought to have paid the employee either over the course of the period of reasonable notice or as pay in lieu of notice. Therefore, in accordance with the exception which is carved out in s. 68(1) for &ldquo;salary, wages or other remuneration&rdquo;, this money is not divisible among a bankrupt's creditors and does not vest in the trustee. The right of action is the means of attaining these damages and is similarly exempt. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>51. In the result, on the authority of <EM>Wallace</EM>, Mr. Justice Charron concluded in <EM>Landry</EM> that, to the extent the arbitrator's award related to the pay Landry should have received in lieu of notice, the monies would constitute &ldquo;wages&rdquo; for the purpose of the section 67(1)(b) exception (the exemption provision). However, he also found, based on <EM>Wallace</EM>, that section 67 must be considered in conjunction with section 68. He then turned to a consideration of the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <EM>Marzetti</EM>.</P>
<P>52. In <EM>Landry</EM>, Mr. Justice Charron noted the amendments which had been made to sections 67 and 68 since <EM>Marzetti</EM> and <EM>Wallace</EM> were decided. Under the version of section 68 considered in those cases, the Supreme Court of Canada had authoritatively determined that section 68 superceded the provisions of section 67 insofar as &ldquo;salary, wages or other remuneration&rdquo; from employment were concerned. The question then considered by Mr. Justice Charron was whether the same interpretation applied to the version of section 68 before him. That version of section 68 appears at Part 1, TAB K. He first noted that the amended version of section 68 which he was considering differed from the former version in a number of respects. Firstly, the new version did not refer to &ldquo;salary, wages or other remuneration&rdquo;, but to &ldquo;total income&rdquo;. Total income was defined as including &ldquo;notwithstanding section 67(1)(b) and (b.1), all revenues of a bankrupt of whatever nature or source&rdquo;. The new section still allowed the trustee to apply to the court for a determination of the amount that a bankrupt was required to pay to the estate of the bankrupt out of his or her total income, but &ldquo;an elaborate procedure must be followed&rdquo; before such an application was made. After reviewing this new procedure, Mr. Justice Charron concluded in <EM>Landry</EM> that the reasoning in <EM>Marzetti</EM> and <EM>Wallace</EM> that led to the conclusion that section 68 was a complete code with respect to wages applied equally to the new section 68 (paragraph 30). This meant that section 67 was superceded by the provisions of the current section 68 insofar as the &ldquo;total income&rdquo; of the bankrupt was concerned and therefore it followed that, as in <EM>Wallace</EM>, Ms. Landry's claim against her former employer and any consequent award relating to lost wages did not automatically vest in the trustee under sections 67 and 71. Resort could only be had to section 68 for payment of any portion thereof to the estate of the bankrupt.</P>
<P>53. Mr. Justice Charron did consider the transitional provisions and decided that the &ldquo;new&rdquo; section 68 applied, rather than the former section 68. Respectfully, we do not agree with his interpretation of the transitional provision, but for our purposes it does not matter.</P>
<P>54. Finally, the court in <EM>Landry</EM> considered whether the trustee was precluded from resorting to section 68 of the BIA by the fact that Ms. Landry had been discharged from bankruptcy, and found that the trustee was not. What is interesting is that the court throughout proceeded on the assumption that the award for wrongful dismissal, to the extent that it included a portion for lost wages, was subject to Ms. Landry's bankruptcy notwithstanding that the damages for lost wages would not be actually paid until sometime after her discharge. In other words, the court viewed it on an accrual basis rather than a cash received basis.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Chronological Review of Other Decided Cases re: DTC's and Income Tax Refunds</UNDER></TI>
<P>55. We now turn to a discussion of other decided cases, in approximate chronological order, which pertain to disability tax credits and the nature of the income tax refunds received. There is a group of cases dealing with &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo; which we will discuss at the end.</P>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Ali</EM> (1987)</UNDER></TI>
<P>56. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Ali</SOC><CITE>[1987] O.J. No. 2243</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 4</BOLD>, was a 1987 decision of Mr. Justice Saunders of the Ontario Supreme Court. In this case, the bankrupt had suffered a heart attack and was receiving monthly payments equivalent to 70% of his salary, up to a maximum of $4,000 per month, under a &ldquo;group disability income policy&rdquo; issued by a Canadian life insurance company to his employer, a Canadian chartered bank, as policyholder, with the bank responsible for the premiums. So long as the disability continued, the bankrupt was entitled to continue to receive payments until either death or attainment of retirement age. The payments were made monthly, in arrears, and the bankrupt was required, by the terms of the policy, to provide the insurer with medical and other proof to establish entitlement. As Justice Saunders put it, &ldquo;the document may fairly be described as an income replacement policy&rdquo; (paragraph 2).</P>
<P>57. In <EM>Ali</EM>, the trustee argued that the disability payments were not &ldquo;other remuneration&rdquo; within the meaning of what was then section 48, now section 68 (at the time, section 48 was substantially similar to the section 68 considered in <EM>Marzetti</EM>). The trustee also argued that because the payments were not received from the employer, but rather the insurer, section 68 did not apply. Finally, the trustee argued the bank was neither employing nor using the services of the bankrupt. The court did not accept these submissions. Mr. Justice Saunders found that the bankrupt remained an employee of the bank; the bank had entered into an agreement with the insurer to provide payments to employees who were disabled from working; and those payments were to replace income that would otherwise be payable. He found that the disability payments were &ldquo;other remuneration&rdquo; within the meaning of section 68.</P>
<P>58. We think these conclusions are sound. However, what interested us in the <EM>Ali</EM> decision was the justice's response to the argument that the payments under the disability income policy were in the nature of payments received in compensation for bodily injury or &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo;. At paragraph 3 of his decision, Mr. Justice Saunders did not accept this argument. He agreed that payments received in compensation for bodily injury were not property of a bankrupt divisible among his creditors. However, he found that payments under the policy were not made to compensate the bankrupt for pain and suffering, but rather to partially replace income he would otherwise have received.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Riel</EM> (1992)</UNDER></TI>
<P>59. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Riel</SOC><CITE>[1992] O.J. No. 714</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 5</BOLD>, was a 1992 decision of Mr. Justice Ground of the Ontario Court of Justice (General Division). We note that his decision was appealed to the Ontario Court of Appeal, and the appeal was dismissed, without reasons.</P>
<P>60. In this case, prior to his bankruptcy, Mr. Riel was employed as a salesman with Re/Max and the bankrupt and Re/Max had entered into an employment agreement which provided that when any property listed with Re/Max was sold as a result of the employee's negotiations, the employee would be paid 95% of the commissions earned. It further provided that the employee's share of the commissions would become due and payable to the employee only once they were collected by Re/Max.</P>
<P>61. Several agreements of purchase and sale for some condominium units owned by a developer were executed before Mr. Riel's assignment into bankruptcy, but the actual closings did not occur until after the date of bankruptcy. A dispute then arose between Re/Max and the developer as to payment of the commissions, which was eventually settled. Re/Max was holding the portion of the settlement applicable to Mr. Riel's commissions in trust pending court direction.</P>
<P>62. Mr. Justice Ground acknowledged there did not appear to be any dispute that the relationship between Re/Max and the bankrupt was that of employer/employee, and the bankrupt's remuneration pursuant to such agreement was solely in the form of commissions. Counsel for the trustee argued that section 68 of the BIA applied only where a bankrupt was in receipt of or entitled to receive salary, wages or other remuneration from a person employing or using the services of <UNDER>the bankrupt</UNDER>, and Riel was not a bankrupt when he was employed and performed the services in respect of which the commissions are payable. Mr. Justice Ground accepted this argument and held that section 68, as it then read, was not intended to apply to remuneration for services rendered prior to the date of bankruptcy.</P>
<P>63. Respectfully, we do not think his decision on this point was correct. We note that <CASEREF><SOC>Re Riel</SOC></CASEREF> was decided <UNDER>before</UNDER> the <EM>Marzetti</EM> decision, and while Marzetti was concerned with an income tax refund payable in respect of post-bankruptcy earnings, we do not read <EM>Marzetti's</EM> conclusions that narrowly. Furthermore, in concluding that the bankrupt's commissions were property divisible by reason of section 67, Mr. Justice Ground gave no consideration to any possible provincial exemptions applicable to wages or other remuneration.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Burton</EM> (1994)</UNDER></TI>
<P>64. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Burton</SOC><YEAR>1994</YEAR><CITE>27 CBR (3d) 238</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 6</BOLD>, was a decision of Registrar Ferron of the Ontario Court of Justice (General Division). In that case, the bankrupt received Canada Pension Plan disability benefits. Registrar Ferron found that such payments were remuneration which could be ordered to be paid to the trustee under section 68 of the BIA. He noted that under the Canada Pension Plan, CPP disability benefit payments were exempt from attachment and could not be assigned or charged, and the provisions of the Ontario <EM>Pension Benefits Act</EM> were to the same effect, yet found that &ldquo;these provisions are not effective against the trustee, nor is there any provision of the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM> which would exempt such payments&rdquo; (paragraph 4). Perhaps he meant that because the amounts were subject to section 68, the provisions of section 67(b) would not apply. In any case, his conclusion that such payments are remuneration subject to section 68, as it then read, does seem correct and, in that event, the exempt character of such payments could presumably be taken into account by the court. However, that was not discussed by Registrar Ferron in <CASEREF><SOC>Re Burton</SOC></CASEREF>.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Neufeld</EM> (1993)</UNDER></TI>
<P>65. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Neufeld</SOC><YEAR>1993</YEAR><CITE>CarswellAlta 548</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 7</BOLD>, was a 1993 decision of Registrar Alberstat of the Alberta Court of Queen's Bench. We note that the writer acted as counsel for the bankrupt in the <EM>Neufeld</EM> case. The facts in <EM>Neufeld</EM> were very similar to this case. The bankrupt's child was legally blind, and sometime after Mr. Neufeld was discharged from bankruptcy, he was advised to apply for a disability tax credit and deductions for his son for the current year and previous taxation years. He filed returns claiming the DTC and received a tax refund.</P>
<P>66. <EM>Neufeld</EM> was decided before <EM>Marzetti</EM>. There were no submissions made to Registrar Alberstat as to whether the income tax refund resulting from claiming the disability tax credit was &ldquo;property&rdquo; or &ldquo;income&rdquo;, and there was no discussion of whether such refund was subject to sections 67 or 68. Instead, the argument turned on the fact that anyone applying for a disability tax credit required a certificate from a qualified medical practitioner which confirmed that the disabled person had a prolonged impairment and was markedly restricted in his activities of daily living. Registrar Alberstat noted that, unlike other tax credits, the disability tax credit was not dependent upon receipts.</P>
<P>67. At paragraph 13 of his decision, Registrar Alberstat said the following:
<QUOTE><P>The tax credit is personal to the person disabled. It lives and dies with that disabled person. The clear policy reason allowing the transfer of unused amounts of the disability tax credit to a parent or spouse wholly or partially supporting that disabled person is to supply financial relief for the support and maintenance of that disabled person.</P></QUOTE>
He found that it would, unfair and inequitable for creditors to benefit financially from the disability of a child or spouse of a bankrupt. He found that the tax credit was personal to the disabled person, for the support and maintenance of that disabled person, and quite independent of the supporting parent or spouse's income or liabilities.</P>
<P>68. The arguments presented to Registrar Alberstat were entirely equitable. An analogy was drawn to damages for pain and suffering, and the court was referred to <CASEREF><SOC>Re Hollister</SOC></CASEREF>, a leading case on the subject, which is discussed below. In <CASEREF><SOC>Re Hollister</SOC></CASEREF>, Mr. Justice Fisher said the following:
<QUOTE><P>The law is well settled that the Bankruptcy Act never intended to increase the assets of an insolvent for division amongst his creditors, of monies recovered in an action for personal injuries, as these monies are awarded as damages to the debtor for his pain, suffering and loss of comfort of life, to pay his physician, nurses and hospital expenses, and to compensate him whilst he is incapacitated from earning a living for himself and his family ... Causes of action arising from bodily or mentally suffering, such as actions for assault, seduction, criminal conversation, and damages for personal injuries, remain in the bankrupt.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>69. Registrar Alberstat also referred to the decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Ritenberg v. Crown Trust Co.</SOC></CASEREF>, which was to the same effect, also discussed below.</P>
<P>70. The argument made before Registrar Alberstat was that if it was not for the disability of Mr. Neufeld's son, there would be no entitlement to a disability tax credit. The refund generated by the disability tax credit was intended to provide additional support for the child while he was incapacitated. It seemed then, and still seems, to be directly analogous to amounts awarded to alleviate personal suffering. In many ways &ldquo;compensation&rdquo; in this context does not mean a windfall so much as additional monies to meet higher expenses. It is also our view that Registrar Alberstat's view of the policy reasons behind a disability tax credit were correct, and in this respect, at least, subsequent cases have agreed with him. Also, when Registrar Alberstat said the disability tax credit &ldquo;lived and died with the disabled person&rdquo;, he meant, in our view, that if there was no disability, there would be no credit. However, the essence of his decision was that tax refunds received by the bankrupt by reason of a disabled child who was being supported partially or wholly by the bankrupt were not the bankrupt's property. They were, in effect, the property of the disabled child, although claimed by the parent for his child's benefit. He also found that a constructive trust argument may apply.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Sobieski</EM> (1997)</UNDER></TI>
<P>71. The decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Re Neufeld</SOC></CASEREF> has been criticized by a number of subsequently decided cases. One of these was <CASEREF><SOC>Re Sobieski</SOC><YEAR>1997</YEAR><CITE>2 CBR (4th) 70</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 8</BOLD>, a decision of Registrar Lee of the Manitoba Court of Queen's Bench, which was subsequently upheld by Mr. Justice Kennedy of that court.</P>
<P>72. In <EM>Sobieski</EM>, the facts were substantially similar to ours, except the bankrupt had a disabled mother. In that case, the bankrupt argued that the tax refund was never her property; if she did acquire an interest in the refund, it was not until after her discharge from bankruptcy; and if she acquired an interest in the refund prior to her discharge, then it was as a constructive trustee for her mother. The bankrupt relied on the <EM>Neufeld</EM> decision. In this case, the tax refunds were applicable to income earned by the bankrupt prior to the date of bankruptcy.</P>
<P>73. The trustee argued that during the years preceding her bankruptcy, the bankrupt had incurred obligations for which claims remained outstanding at the date of bankruptcy, and it would be unfair and inequitable for the creditors not to have the benefit of income earned in those years, unless there was some express provision of the <EM>Bankruptcy Act</EM> which excluded the refunds from property available to creditors. Registrar Lee agreed with the submissions of the trustee. He concluded, at paragraph 14, &ldquo;if the applicant had claimed the disability tax credit prior to her bankruptcy, she would have more disposable income and would have been able to pay more of her debts. If the bankrupt was truly contributing to the support of her parents, presumably some of the debt incurred was for the benefit of the parents.&rdquo; He found that the subject refunds were property of the bankrupt, subject to distribution among the bankrupt's creditors.</P>
<P>74. The Registrar's decision was appealed to Mr. Justice Kennedy, who dismissed the appeal [<CASEREF><SOC>Re Sobieski</SOC><YEAR>1997</YEAR><CITE>2 CBR (4th) 70</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 9</BOLD>]. He noted the refunds were received by the bankrupt following her bankruptcy in respect of tax credits which could have been applied for at the time of bankruptcy and, accordingly, he was satisfied they fell within the provisions of section 67 of the BIA. It is interesting to note that both Registrar Lee and Justice Kennedy proceeded on the basis that the relevant timing was the period to which the tax refunds related, and not when they were actually received. At paragraph 9, Mr. Justice Kennedy said:
<QUOTE><P>The Act clearly contemplates that the monies that are within the control of the bankrupt at the time of bankruptcy are available for the creditors. There is no doubt either that these monies would, if they had been applied for during the bankruptcy, have been deemed bankrupt's property as opposed to her mother's.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>75. Neither Registrar Lee nor Mr. Justice Kennedy in <EM>Sobieski</EM> considered <EM>Marzetti</EM>. There was no discussion of whether the tax refunds could be &ldquo;income&rdquo; as opposed to &ldquo;property&rdquo;, nor was there any discussion of the analogy drawn between disability tax credits and the &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo; cases. There was also no mention of possible provincial exemptions. While Registrar Lee noted the constructive trust argument, he simply rejected it without analysis.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Clifford</EM> (1997)</UNDER></TI>
<P>76. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Clifford</SOC><YEAR>1997</YEAR><CITE>46 CBR (3d) 132</CITE></CASEREF>, which is attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 10</BOLD>, was a decision of Deputy Registrar Stevens of the Ontario Court of Justice, General Division. In this case, the bankrupt's employment was terminated prior to his bankruptcy and he subsequently received vacation pay, termination pay and deductions after a conditional order of discharge had been granted.</P>
<P>77. In <EM>Clifford</EM>, Deputy Registrar Stevens relied on 3 Ontario decisions, including <EM>Riel</EM>, to find that section 68 did not apply to pre-bankruptcy earnings. Again, this was a case where the court assumed that the period with respect to which the earnings related, and not the time the amounts were actually paid, was determinative. There was no discussion in <EM>Clifford</EM> of the <EM>Marzetti</EM> decision, nor was there any discussion of the exemption applicable to wages in Ontario or section 67(1)(b) of the BIA. Given the broad language in section 68 as it read at the time (the version considered in <EM>Marzetti</EM>), and given that we do not read <EM>Marzetti</EM> that narrowly, this decision does not seem correct.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Hynes</EM> (2000)</UNDER></TI>
<P>78. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Hynes</SOC><YEAR>2000</YEAR><CITE>20 CBR (4th) 98</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 11</BOLD>, was a decision of Registrar Hill of the Nova Scotia Supreme Court. In this case, the bankrupt qualified for a pay equity payment which she received after she had made an assignment in bankruptcy but before her discharge. For the purposes of his decision, Registrar Hill characterized the payment as pre-bankruptcy earnings. That being the case, he then considered it necessary to consider whether or not the trustee's application for a conditional order of discharge, which sought to have Ms. Hynes pay all or part of the pay equity amount to the trustee, should instead have been made pursuant to section 68 of the BIA. The version of section 68 considered in <EM>Hynes</EM> was the <EM>Landry</EM> version, that is, it contained a definition of &ldquo;total income&rdquo;, but without the current version's limitation of &ldquo;total income&rdquo; to amounts earned or received by the bankrupt during the period of bankruptcy.</P>
<P>79. In our respectful submission, <EM>Hynes</EM> was a very well-reasoned decision. Registrar Hill squarely considered the issue of whether section 68 applied to both pre-bankruptcy and post-bankruptcy wages and he correctly, in our view, concluded that section 68, as it then read, did apply to both pre-bankruptcy and post-bankruptcy wages.</P>
<P>80. Registrar Hill referred to a very useful article which addressed the question written by Robert A. Klotz, &ldquo;Who Gets the Bankrupt's Pre-Bankrutcy Earnings?&rdquo; (2000) 15 CBR (4<SUP>th</SUP>) 153 (the &ldquo;Klotz article&rdquo;). The Klotz article is attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 12</BOLD>. In his article, Mr. Klotz analyzed, in particular, the approach taken by the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Marzetti, Wallace</EM> and <CASEREF><SOC>Ramgotra (Trustee of) v. North American Life Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[196] 1 SCR 325</CITE></CASEREF>. The headnote from <EM>Ramgotra</EM> and the relevant pages of that decision dealing with these issues are attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 13</BOLD>.</P>
<P>81. In <EM>Hynes</EM>, Registrar Hill said the following, at paragraph 7, with which we agree:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Marzetti</EM> dealt with post-bankruptcy income, in the form of an income tax refund. However, nowhere in that case did the Court specifically restrict its findings as to the applicability of s. 68 to post-bankruptcy earnings. The Court found that s. 68 was a substantive rather than procedural modification to the scheme in existence prior to its enactment. This being the case, the Court held that s. 68 was intended to operate as a complete code in respect of a bankrupt's salary, wages, or other remuneration. Consequently, those forms of property did not fall within s. 67(c) of the Bankruptcy Act (as it then was titled) and were not to be considered &ldquo;property of a bankrupt divisible, amongst his creditors&rdquo; for the purposes of s. 67 (at p. 644, W.W.R.)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>82. Registrar Hill went on to say that the Supreme Court of substantive provision, rather than procedural, because that better reflected the language of s, 68 and &ldquo;as a substantive provision, would more effectively remedy the mischief which led to its enactment.&rdquo; (paragraph 8)</P>
<P>83. Registrar Hill acknowledged that section 68, as reviewed in <EM>Marzetti</EM>, and the version of section 68 before him, were somewhat different, since the amended version before him came into force on April 30<SUP>th</SUP>, 1998. However, neither section 68 as it was in <EM>Marzetti</EM>, nor as it read before him, specifically differentiated between pre and post-bankruptcy income (paragraph 9).</P>
<P>84. Registrar Hill also reviewed the decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Ramgotra</EM>, where the court had occasion to refer to section 68. While section 68 played no part in that decision, Registrar Hill stated there could be no doubt that the court in <EM>Ramgotra</EM> regarded section 68 as dealing only with after-acquired wages, salary or other remuneration. However, in the <EM>Wallace</EM> case, which the Registrar also considered, the court found that Wallace's right to sue for severance pay arose not because of the time of the acquisition of a property right in that payment, but rather because of the nature of the property in question, i.e. wages (paragraph 16). As noted in the Klotz article, &ldquo;Wallace won not because his claim was after-acquired property, but because it derived from wages and thus fell within section 68&rdquo;.</P>
<P>85. In <EM>Hynes</EM>, Registrar Hill concluded that nothing in the amendments to section 68 which came into force in 1998 led him to conclude that section 68 was other than the substantive provision the Supreme Court of Canada found the prior version to be and, furthermore, section 68 had application to both pre and post-bankruptcy income. As he noted in paragraph 19 of his decision:
<QUOTE><P>If we are dealing with income from employment of &ldquo;whatever nature or source&rdquo;, surely we are dealing with both pre and post-bankruptcy income.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>86. Accordingly, at paragraph 23, Registrar Hill concluded that the pay equity settlement, which was paid after the date of bankruptcy, but which related to the period prior to bankruptcy, was &ldquo;wages&rdquo; and fell within section 68. Based on section 68 as it read at that time, we think he was entirely correct.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Cole</EM> (2001)</UNDER></TI>
<P>87. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Cole</SOC><CITE>[2001] NSJ No. 155</CITE></CASEREF> was another decision of Registrar Hill, and attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 14.</BOLD> In this case, Dr. Cole was involved in a motor vehicle accident and, as a result, was pursuing a claim for lost income. The lost income claim would involve both past and future lost income. The trustee brought an application for advice and directions as to the procedures to be followed by the trustee to seek the proceeds of the personal injury claim to the extent it included an amount for logs of income. The trustee applied on the basis that such an award for loss of income would be governed by section 68 of the BIA.</P>
<P>88. At paragraph 23, Registrar Hill noted that the loss of income claim being pursued by the bankrupt involved lost income arising before the date of her assignment in bankruptcy, during the period in which she is a bankrupt, and potentially for that time after she is discharged. He referred to his earlier decision in H<EM>ynes</EM> in which he concluded that the words &ldquo;total income&rdquo;, then defined in section 68 of the BIA, referred to all revenue of a bankrupt from whatever nature or source and included not only income accruing during the period of the bankruptcy, but income accruing prior to the date of bankruptcy.</P>
<P>89. In <EM>Cole</EM>, Registrar Hill also considered the Ontario Court of Appeal's decision in <EM>Landry</EM>, which had been released shortly before he rendered his decision in <EM>Hynes</EM> and of which he was not aware at the time he made his decision in <EM>Hynes</EM>. He concluded the decision in <EM>Landry</EM> &ldquo;confirms and comforts me in the decision I reached in <EM>Hynes</EM>&rdquo; (paragraph 26). He observed that the decision of the Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Landry</EM> both &ldquo;implicitly and explicitly&rdquo; confirmed the view taken by him that section 68 had application to both pre and post-bankruptcy income. [Again, this case was decided before section 68 was further amended in 2009 to include the qualification it contains now, which limits &ldquo;total income&rdquo; to only those amounts earned or received during the period of bankruptcy.]</P>
<P>90. At paragraph 34 of his decision, Registrar Hill noted that the court in <EM>Landry</EM> reviewed the definition of a &ldquo;bankrupt&rdquo; and concluded the term not only referred to the legal status of the person during the period of bankruptcy, but was also descriptive of an individual who had made an assignment. Thus, after discharge, a person might still be described as a &ldquo;bankrupt&rdquo;, although one who had been discharged. Similarly, we think the reference to amounts received &ldquo;by the bankrupt&rdquo; in section 68 does not preclude section 68 from applying to amounts applicable to the period prior to the date of bankruptcy. In that regard, we submit the narrow view of the language taken by Mr. Justice Ground in <EM>Riel</EM>, for example, was incorrect.</P>
<P>91. In <EM>Cole</EM>, at paragraph 35, Registrar Hill observed that the court in <EM>Landry</EM> had noted that, &ldquo;(T)here was nothing in the language of section 68 which would restrict its application to the time frame between the date of bankruptcy and the date of the bankrupt's discharge. What is important, in the view of the Ontario Court of Appeal, is the nature of the property in question, not the period of time in which it is acquired or received.&rdquo; As previously observed, the current version of section 68 now contains such a restriction.</P>
<P>92. Finally, on the issue of timing, Registrar Hill said the following at paragraph 38:
<QUOTE><P>In my opinion, the purpose of s. 68 is to allow a trustee access to a bankrupt's income for the benefit of the bankrupt's creditors. Where monies to be received by the bankrupt can properly be characterized as &ldquo;income&rdquo;, I see no reason to artificially deny access merely because the income will be received after discharge. The important point to consider is &ldquo;when was the income earned&rdquo; and not &ldquo;when was it received&rdquo;. Accountants have understood the &ldquo;accrual method&rdquo; of accounting for centuries. The same principals [sic] apply here. &ldquo;Income&rdquo; earned prior to bankruptcy is income earned at a time when the bankrupt owed a contractual obligation to the creditors to pay the debts owed to them. &ldquo;Income&rdquo; earned during bankruptcy is income earned during a period where a statutory duty under s. 68 may exist to contribute some of that income towards the estate for the benefit of the creditors. It would simply be wrong to allow a bankrupt to escape his or her obligations where by design or circumstance receipt of the income is delayed until after discharge. Section 68 as it now reads avoids that result.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Nixon</EM> (2001)</UNDER></TI>
<P>93. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Nixon</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>SKQB 221</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 15</BOLD>, was a decision of Registrar Herauf (as he then was) of the Saskatchewan Court of Queen's Bench. In this case, the facts were very similar to ours and practically identical to <EM>Neufeld</EM>, in that the bankrupt had a son who was legally blind. Registrar Herauf referred to the <EM>Neufeld</EM> and <EM>Sobieski</EM> decisions and decided to follow <EM>Sobieski</EM>. He accordingly found that the refunds to be paid would be property of the bankrupt estate and not the disabled child. In <EM>Nixon</EM>, there was no discussion of whether the tax refund could be considered &ldquo;income&rdquo; as opposed to &ldquo;property&rdquo;, nor was there any reference to <EM>Marzetti, Wallace or Ramgotra</EM>. Neither <EM>Hynes</EM> nor <EM>Cole</EM> were referred to the Registrar. Also, there was no discussion of provincial exemptions which could apply by reason of section 67(1)(b).</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>T.A.H., also cited as Henderson</EM> (2003)</UNDER></TI>
<P>94. In <CASEREF><SOC>Re H. (T.A.)</SOC></CASEREF>, sometimes also cited as <CASEREF><SOC>Re Henderson</SOC><YEAR>2003</YEAR><CITE>ABQB 877</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 16</BOLD>, Registrar Waller of the Alberta Court of Queen's Bench considered facts very similar to ours and <EM>Neufeld</EM>. He observed, at paragraph 4:
<QUOTE><P>Unlike other tax credits, the disability tax credit is not dependant on the taxpayer producing receipts for actual expenses. The credit is based on a formula and the tax credit is generated from the income of the parent who is wholly supporting the child.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>95. In <CASEREF><SOC>Re H. (T.A.)</SOC></CASEREF>, neither the trustee nor the bankrupt were represented by legal counsel. There was no consideration of whether the income tax refunds were &ldquo;income&rdquo; as opposed to &ldquo;property&rdquo;. Indeed, there was no reference to section 68 of the BIA at all. He was referred to the decisions in <EM>Neufeld, Nixon, Sobieski</EM> and <EM>Burton</EM> but not <EM>Marzetti, Landry, Hynes</EM> or <EM>Cole</EM>.</P>
<P>96. At paragraph 16 of his reasons, Registrar Waller observed that under the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, certain payments are exempted by law from the operation of the BIA, such as GST credits. However, he noted: &ldquo;the fact the disability tax credits are not specifically exempted by operation of law did not end the matter. For example, damages for pain and suffering to a bankrupt have long been recognized as not forming part of his or her estate&rdquo; (paragraph 16). In this respect, we suggest he was entirely correct.</P>
<P>97. In the result, Registrar Waller found that the tax credit was not personal to the person disabled, but the property of the taxpayer who supported that disabled person. And while he referred to the old English decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Beckham v. Drake</SOC></CASEREF>, which enunciated the principle that damages for pain and suffering are not available to creditors, he did not analyze or apply it.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Bolz</EM> (2004)</UNDER></TI>
<P>98. <CASEREF><SOC>Re: Bolz</SOC><YEAR>2004</YEAR><CITE>BCSC 1702</CITE></CASEREF> was a decision of Mr. Justice Romilly of the British Columbia Supreme Court, and is attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 17</BOLD>. In <EM>Bolz</EM>, the bankrupt had applied for disability tax credits after the date of his discharge and received a refund. The funds in question arose from both the pre and post-bankruptcy tax returns and the disability tax credit reassessment. Ignoring for the purpose of these submissions the issue pertaining to an agreement signed by the bankrupt in favour of the trustee directing that post-bankruptcy refunds be paid into the estate, which he found was of no force or effect, what is of interest in this decision is the court's approach to the pre and post-bankruptcy tax refunds.</P>
<P>99. With respect to the pre-bankruptcy tax refunds, Mr. Justice Romilly simply stated that section 71(2) of the BIA [now section 71] applied and these refunds vested in the trustee.</P>
<P>100. With respect to the post-bankruptcy tax refunds, Mr. Justice Romilly considered the decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Marzetti</EM>, which held that a post-bankruptcy income tax refund retained its character as wages for the purposes of section 68 of the Act. He then turned to a consideration of the disability tax credit cases, including <EM>Neufeld, Sobieski, Nixon</EM> and <EM>Henderson (T.A.H.)</EM>. Neither the <EM>Hynes</EM> nor <EM>Cole</EM> decisions were presented to His Lordship.</P>
<P>101. In the result, Mr. Justice Romilly read <EM>Marzetti</EM> very narrowly, in our respectful submission, and found that <EM>Marzetti</EM> &ldquo;takes no position on the status of a pre-bankruptcy tax refund, but instead deals exclusively with a post-bankruptcy refund&rdquo; (paragraph 22). However, he followed <EM>Marzetti</EM> in finding that the &ldquo;income tax refund portion&rdquo; of the post-bankruptcy tax return retained its character as income for the purposes of section 68, and could be accessed by the trustee only by means of an application pursuant to section 68.</P>
<P>102. Mr. Justice Romilly then dealt separately with the &ldquo;disability tax credit portion&rdquo;, that is, the portion of the refunds that arose as a result of the claims for disability tax credits. He found that the &ldquo;tax credit refund&rdquo; representing the pre-bankruptcy years formed part of the property of the bankrupt and vested in the trustee. He did not consider any provincial exemptions which may apply to these refunds, if they were to be characterized as &ldquo;wages&rdquo;. Perhaps that is because he decided, in regards to the post-bankruptcy disability tax credit refund, that they were not &ldquo;wages&rdquo;. He drew a distinction between the post-bankruptcy tax refund that was considered in <EM>Marzetti</EM> and the post-bankruptcy disability tax credit refund before him. In his view, the DTC refund stemmed not from an &ldquo;overpayment of wages&rdquo;, but from a disability tax credit. He saw this as an important distinction &ldquo;as this credit is considered by the CCRA to be a non-refundable, fixed credit to aid those living with a disability or caring for individuals with a disability&rdquo;, (paragraph 31) He gave no consideration to the fact that the refund which arose as a result of the disability tax credit being claimed was a return of income on which the bankrupt had previously paid tax. Respectfully, we think his conclusion on this point was incorrect.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Bowerbank-Buckley</EM> (2007)</UNDER></TI>
<P>103. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Bowerbank-Buckley</SOC><CITE>[2007] O.J. No. 5722</CITE></CASEREF>, was a decision of Deputy Registrar Diamond of the Ontario Superior Court of Justice, and is attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 18</BOLD>. In this case, he was applying the <EM>Landry</EM> versions of sections 67 and 68. There were two cases before him, both concerning bankrupts who were parents of a disabled child and who, after being discharged from their bankruptcies, became aware they were entitled to disability tax credits for periods prior to, during and after their respective bankruptcies. In other words, the facts were substantially the same as the case at bar.</P>
<P>104. Registrar Diamond clearly understood the issue before him. At paragraph 4, he said:
<QUOTE><P>The question at issue is how are the funds to be characterized in the context of the bankruptcy and discharge therefrom. There are three possible answers: the first is that the funds are property of a third party and held in trust, and are thus exempt property pursuant to section 67(1)(a) of the [BIA] and do not vest in the trustee; the second is that they are property of the bankrupt's estate, as defined in section 2 and set out in sections 67 and 71 of the BIA and vest in the trustee in bankruptcy for distribution to the bankrupt's creditors; or third, the funds are income of the bankrupt and thus should be dealt with pursuant to section 68 of the BIA.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>105. On the question of whether the refunds were property of a third party [the child] and held in trust, Registrar Diamond agreed with Registrar Waller in <EM>Henderson (T.A.H.)</EM> that these funds were not held in trust for the disabled child. He spent some time discussing section 67(2) of the BIA and statutory deemed trusts and concluded that under the relevant provisions of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, there was no deemed trust for refunds payable as a result of claiming a disability tax credit.</P>
<P>106. Registrar Diamond was also of the view that the disability tax credit provisions in the ITA did not create a &ldquo;trust proper&rdquo;. He stated, correctly in our view, that a clear legislative intent was required for the creation of a deemed trust and what the ITA provision did was reduce the amount of tax payable by the taxpayer. &ldquo;It does not stipulate how the resulting tax savings are to be spent or whom they are to be spent on&rdquo; (paragraph 12). He had also earlier noted in his decision, at paragraph 9, that &ldquo;one of the main objections to labelling refund amounts arising from this credit as &lsquo;trust funds&rsquo; has been that parents or guardians do not need to account for their use of the funds and are permitted to simply incorporate the money into their household finances.&rdquo;</P>
<P>107. On whether the income tax refunds arising from the disability tax credits for the pre-bankruptcy period were &ldquo;income&rdquo; or &ldquo;property&rdquo;, Registrar Diamond regarded himself as bound by <EM>Landry</EM>. In his view, the Court of Appeal in <EM>Landry</EM> had concluded that the damages awarded after bankruptcy from a &ldquo;chose in action&rdquo; for wrongful dismissal that occurred before bankruptcy were not property, but income. However, respectfully, we think he misreads <EM>Landry</EM> when he views that decision as &ldquo;in effect, dealing with the funds that flow from employment and income on a receipt basis, not an accrual basis&rdquo; (paragraph 17). He read <EM>Landry</EM> as suggesting that the fact entitlement to the tax credit in the case before him arose prior to the bankruptcy was not determinative of whether the funds are property or income, and this conclusion was &ldquo;somewhat controversial&rdquo; (paragraph 16).</P>
<P>108. With respect to Registrar Diamond, we do not think that was the court's conclusion in <EM>Landry</EM> at all. We further think Registrar Diamond's suggestion that if income earned prior to bankruptcy had been deposited into the bankrupt's bank account the day before the assignment, then those funds would have been considered property, not income, was incorrect. If income earned prior to bankruptcy had been deposited into the bankrupt's bank account the day before the assignment, those funds would likely still retain their character as income and presumably be subject to provincial exemptions if section 68 did not apply. Of course, at the time <EM>Bowerbank-Buckley</EM> was decided, section 68 did apply to pre-bankruptcy income on the authority of <EM>Landry</EM>.</P>
<P>109. We submit Registrar Diamond was correct in his conclusion that the Court of Appeal in <EM>Landry</EM> had decided that it was clear from <EM>Wallace</EM> and <EM>Marzetti</EM> that section 68 applied to wages attributable to the period before bankruptcy &ldquo;because of the nature of the property in question, regardless of the timing of the acquisition of the property or for the fact that the payment is made in a lump sum&rdquo;, (paragraph 19)</P>
<P>110. Finally, Registrar Diamond considered the nature of a disability tax credit and considered the reasons of Mr. Justice Romilly in <EM>Bolz</EM>. We have earlier cited, at page 6 of this brief, his quotation of Professor David Duff in that author's McGill Law Journal article <EM>Disability and the Income Tax</EM> and his view of the true character of a disability tax credit.</P>
<P>111. Registrar Diamond went on to observe at paragraph 28 of his reasons, citing with approval another article by a different professor, the following:
<QUOTE><P>The motivation behind the DTC is ... to allow disabled people and those caring for them <UNDER>to keep more of their taxable income in light of the added expenses that they incur</UNDER>. The fact that these expenses are not always itemizable and therefore are not always covered by the medical expense tax credit necessitates the creation of a fixed credit. This should not be interpreted, however, as signifying that the DTC is not connected to income or to expenses, but rather merely indicates its remedial nature. From this one can conclude that the DTC should be treated the same way as a tax refund and included in the income of the bankrupt. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>112. Accordingly, he found that, because the purpose of the DTC was to augment the income of the parent of a disabled child, it was akin to income and should therefore, following <EM>Marzetti</EM>, and <EM>Landry</EM>, be dealt with under section 68 of the BIA as income and not section 67 as property.</P>
<P>113. Registrar Diamond then, in our respectful view, made something of a hard left turn and, in so doing, misapplied the principles in <EM>Landry</EM>. Registrar Diamond held that if the accounting for these refunds was to be done on a receipt basis and not an accrual basis, then these funds were not &ldquo;income of a bankrupt&rdquo; within the meaning of section 68 as it then read, as the taxpayer had been discharged from bankruptcy before there was any awareness of the right to and receipt of the disability tax credit. He then held that the funds were properly payable to the bankrupt to be kept by her to pay for her children's needs.</P>
<P>114. Respectfully, we think that Registrar Diamond was quite correct that refunds generated by disability tax credits should be treated as &ldquo;income&rdquo; and not &ldquo;property&rdquo;. However, we do not agree that <EM>Landry</EM> expected the accounting for such refunds to be done a receipt basis and we submit that any such refunds attributable to the period prior to bankruptcy or during bankruptcy were &ldquo;income&rdquo; to be addressed by the trustee, based on the version of section 68 as it read at the time.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Folk</EM> (2012)</UNDER></TI>
<P>115. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Folk</SOC><YEAR>2012</YEAR><CITE>5 CBR (6th) 137</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 19</BOLD>, was a decision of Mr. Justice Cumming of the Ontario Superior Court of Justice. We include it here because it is an example of a higher court adopting, with approval, Registrar Diamond's analysis of the true character of a disability tax credit refund in <EM>Bowerbank-Buckley</EM>. Mr. Justice Cumming allowed the appeal from a decision by Registrar Nettie in the court below that the pre-bankruptcy refunds in that case were &ldquo;property&rdquo;, and held that the pre-bankruptcy refunds were to be treated as &ldquo;income&rdquo; under section 68.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Ford</EM> (2009)</UNDER></TI>
<P>116. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Ford</SOC><YEAR>2009</YEAR><CITE>53 CBR (5th) 298</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 20</BOLD>, was a decision of Registrar Cregan of the Nova Scotia Supreme Court. We think this decision was very well reasoned and it has been frequently cited.</P>
<P>117. In the case before him, the facts were substantially similar to this case, except that Ms. Ford had a disabled mother.</P>
<P>118. Registrar Cregan began his decision by reviewing the legislative history of section 68, noting the amendments which had been made to section 68 but not yet proclaimed at the time of his decision. He also discussed the character of the disability tax credit which, in the case before him, was sometimes called the &ldquo;caregiver amount&rdquo;. He succinctly described this credit as follows, at paragraphs 7 and 8 of his decision:
<QUOTE><P>In substance both the federal and the Nova Scotia government have decided as a matter of social policy that taxpayers who in their home look after their disabled or aged parents of limited income should be helped with this tax credit which reduces their annual income tax assessments. It is something they are entitled to annually.</P>
<P>The amount is a non-refundable tax credit. A percentage of this credit is deducted from the tax payable. ... The taxpayer can only use the credit to reduce taxes otherwise payable. Any portion of the credit not needed for this purpose is lost. The credit may result in a taxpayer receiving a refund, his or her payroll deductions or quarterly payments being, with the credit, more than needed to pay the taxes assessed. There is clear law, as will be noted later, as to how such refunds will be treated year by year. However, in the present case the refunds arise from later reassessments. What was received is the total of what would have been received had the amount been claimed each year.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>119. Registrar Cregan began his analysis by reviewing the decision in <EM>Marzetti</EM> and noted that it concluded the refund should be considered as &ldquo;wages&rdquo; because it was a return of money which the bankrupt had earned as wages. &ldquo;It is the surplus remaining after taxes are assessed. <UNDER>This surplus is still wages</UNDER>, but is only received once it is no longer needed to pay any outstanding taxes&rdquo; (emphasis added) (paragraph 14).</P>
<P>120. Registrar Cregan also considered the <EM>Landry</EM> decision and found the case was authority for the point that section 68 as it then read applied to income which accrued prior to the bankruptcy but was not received by the time of discharge.</P>
<P>121. Registrar Cregan discussed the decisions in <EM>Bolz, Sobieski</EM> and <EM>Nixon</EM>, as well as <EM>Neufeld</EM>. He noted the trust analysis in <EM>Neufeld</EM> was generally not accepted. He was not inclined to follow the other cases because, in his view, the concern of the court in those decisions was to determine whether the credits were property of the bankrupts as opposed to someone else, namely the disabled person. In his view, that was not the problem before him. Rather, it was a contest between whether the refunds at issue were property of the bankrupt or part of the bankrupt's &ldquo;revenue&rdquo; or &ldquo;total income&rdquo; which, if so, must be processed under section 68 (paragraph 30).</P>
<P>122. He went on to say, at paragraph 37, that whether the funds in question were &ldquo;salary, wages or other remuneration&rdquo; under the old wording of section 68 or &ldquo;total income&rdquo; including &ldquo;all revenue of a bankrupt of whatever nature or source&rdquo; under the wording of section 68 before him, and earned or in some other way crystallized during the bankruptcy period and received during the bankruptcy or after discharge, they were to be distributed under section 68. In his view, this followed clearly from <EM>Marzetti</EM> and it further followed from <EM>Landry</EM> that this applied to funds earned or crystallized before bankruptcy, but not received until after the assignment was made.</P>
<P>123. Registrar Cregan then considered two questions (paragraph 39 and 40). The first was whether the disability tax credit or, as he described it, the &ldquo;caregiver amount&rdquo; fit within &ldquo;all revenue of a bankrupt or whatever nature or source&rdquo; and was thus part of &ldquo;total income&rdquo; under section 68. The second was whether <EM>Landry</EM> should be followed in saying that section 68 applies to funds earned, accrued or otherwise crystallized before the assignment in bankruptcy. He concluded that a wide and generous meaning should be given to what constitutes &ldquo;revenue&rdquo; under section 68. At paragraph 45, he said this:
<QUOTE><P>Does a reasonable meaning of &ldquo;income&rdquo; or &ldquo;revenue&rdquo; considered in the context of s. 68 include these caregiver amounts? I think it does. They arise from the personal circumstances of the bankrupt. They are accruing payments, available yearly, in recognition of certain social goals adopted by the ITA. They recognize extra efforts the taxpayer makes. They come in annually, are modest in amount, intended to help a family in its current needs. I appreciate that to receive the credit one must in fact be assessed income tax against which the credit is set off; otherwise the credit is lost, being non-refundable. However, I do not see this conditional entitlement detracts from its nature as income or revenue. The language of s. 68, particularly the words &ldquo;total&rdquo; and &ldquo;all&rdquo;, and &ldquo;whatever nature or source&rdquo;, I think direct that the benefit of any doubt must be given in favour of including these credits as part of &lsquo;total income&rsquo;.&rdquo;</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>124. As Registrar Cregan observed, if Ms. Ford had been receiving the allowance each year as each accrued, the benefit would have been reflected in the amount of tax she would have had to pay. It would be less. She would then receive a greater refund. Following <EM>Marzetti</EM>, that refund would be income under section 68. He did not think the fact that Ms. Ford did not receive the credits annually but rather as one lump sum made any difference, because he was satisfied that such amounts were revenue caught by section 68 &ldquo;whatever way it is delivered&rdquo;. He answered the first question in the affirmative.</P>
<P>125. As to the second question, and whether section 68 applied to funds earned, accrued or otherwise crystallized before assignment, he observed that if the unproclaimed amendment to section 68 [the amendment which came into force in 2009] was in effect, &ldquo;the task would be quite easy&rdquo; (paragraph 50). He observed the amended version of section 68 defined total income as including &ldquo;a bankrupt's revenues of whatever nature or from whatever source that are earned or received by the bankrupt between the date of the bankruptcy and the date of the bankrupt's discharge&rdquo;. Therefore, as he read what is now the current version of section 68, income which accrued or was earned before bankruptcy but not received between the date of bankruptcy and the date of discharge &ldquo;would apparently not be covered by section 68&rdquo;. He went on to say, &ldquo;I understand this amendment is intended to clarify the confused state of affairs with which I am now addressing.&rdquo; In the result, in the case before him, he followed <EM>Landry</EM> and found that income accrued before bankruptcy was subject to section 68. Whether the 2009 amendments to section 68 &ldquo;clarify the confused state of affairs&rdquo; or not is something this application addresses.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Potter</EM> (2010)</UNDER></TI>
<P>126. There remain to be discussed two bankruptcy cases decided by the Manitoba Court of Queen's Bench. The first is <CASEREF><SOC>Re Potter</SOC><YEAR>2010</YEAR><CITE>MBQB 36</CITE></CASEREF>, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 21</BOLD>, another decision of Registrar Harrison. The case was concerned with disability tax credits claimed only for the years prior to bankruptcy. This case considered the <EM>Landry</EM> versions of sections 67 and 68. Registrar Harrison considered <EM>Marzetti</EM>, but said &ldquo;it must be remembered that <EM>Marzetti</EM> dealt only with post-bankruptcy tax refunds&rdquo; (paragraph 18).</P>
<P>127. Registrar Harrison considered the 2009 amendments to sections 67 and 68, but noted that the unamended versions (the <EM>Landry</EM> versions) were the versions applicable to the case before him. He then concluded, at paragraph 30, that &ldquo;revenue cannot be a tax rebate by definition, nor by the same standard can a tax refund be termed income; rather it is an overpayment of tax&rdquo;. With respect, this statement seems entirely wrong.</P>
<P>128. Registrar Harrison did refer to the decision of Registrar Cregan in <EM>Ford</EM>, but disagreed with his conclusion that section 68 applied to pre-bankruptcy amounts (paragraph 31). He also said at paragraph 32 that &ldquo;(T)he other issue not specifically addressed by Registrar Cregan is the present statutory inclusion of the term &lsquo;any refund owing to the bankrupt under the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>&rsquo; in section 67 in the present amended BIA, and whether that represents a change in the applicable law to the time frame in question&rdquo;. With respect, Registrar Cregan did comment on the amendment to paragraph 67(1)(c), passed in 2007 and proclaimed in 2008, but not applicable to the case before him, at paragraph 47 of his decision, and observed that &ldquo;this would limit the application of his analysis in the future&rdquo;.</P>
<P>129. With respect to Registrar Lee and Registrar Cregan, section 67(1)(c) as it presently reads only specifically includes any refund owing to the bankrupt under the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> &ldquo;<UNDER>in respect of</UNDER> the calendar year ... in which the bankrupt became a bankrupt&rdquo;. This language does <UNDER>not</UNDER> specifically include refunds owing to the bankrupt &ldquo;in respect of the years prior to the date of bankruptcy as &ldquo;property&rdquo; of the bankrupt.</P>
<P>130. As to the decision in <EM>Landry</EM>, Registrar Harrison simply said that he was not convinced that an Ontario appellate decision concerning an action for unjust dismissal was relevant to a Manitoba court dealing with a tax refund issue based on a disability tax credit (paragraph 33).</P>
<P>131. In the result, Registrar Harrison found that Mr. Potter's right to the tax refund &ldquo;was under his full control&rdquo; on the date of his assignment and therefore caught as &ldquo;property&rdquo; within section 67 and it did not possess the character of &ldquo;revenue in that these monies were never withheld by his employer from wages he was earning at this pre-bankruptcy time&rdquo; (paragraph 39). With respect, this decision seems wrong to us.</P>
<P>132. The decision of Registrar Lee was appealed and the appeal was heard by Mr. Justice Menzies [2010] MBQB 83, attached at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 22.</BOLD> In his reasons, Mr. Justice Menzies agreed with Registrar Harrison that the disability tax credit refund was &ldquo;property&rdquo; within the meaning of the BIA. However, he went on to consider whether the disability tax credit should be dealt with as property under section 67 or income subject to section 68. Mr. Justice Menzies referred to the description of the disability tax credit as income set out in <EM>Bowerbank-Buckley</EM>, and also the discussion of such refunds in <EM>Ford</EM>. He found the reasoning of the Registrar in those cases &ldquo;to be very persuasive&rdquo;. At paragraph 12, he said:
<QUOTE><P>The refund generated by the disability tax credit results in a rebate of tax paid or owing by the taxpayer. The tax paid or owing originates from the taxpayer's income. If in fact the taxpayer has not prepaid their tax, any outstanding tax liability is decreased. The fact the money is being returned to the taxpayer after already being received by the CRA does not, in my opinion, cause the funds to lose their status as income. The rebate is a process whereby the taxpayer is allowed to retain a greater portion of their taxable income in any given year in recognition of the unascertained expenses incurred as a caregiver for a disabled person.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>133. The report of Mr. Justice Menzies' decision is confusing because it states that the appeal was dismissed and the decision of Registrar Harrison was affirmed. However, he overruled Registrar Harrison on the question of whether the disability tax credit refunds were income or not; Justice Menzies found they were income and, in this, we think he was correct.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Gabrielle</EM> (2014)</UNDER></TI>
<P>134. <CASEREF><SOC>Re Gabrielle</SOC><YEAR>2014</YEAR><CITE>MBQB 77</CITE></CASEREF>, was another decision of Registrar Harrison and appears at <BOLD>Part 2, TAB 23</BOLD>. In this case, the disability tax credit claimed by the bankrupt pertained to her disabled mother. At paragraph 11, Registrar Harrison stated, &ldquo;The law on the characterization of tax refunds as property or income was recently clarified by amendments to the BIA&rdquo;. He then set out, at paragraph 11, an extract from <EM>Bennett on Bankruptcy</EM>. In that extract, Mr. Bennett stated:
<QUOTE><P>This new section [section 67(1)(c) as it reads today] clearly indicates that for the bankrupt's tax refund for the calendar year the assignment is filed, it is an asset that vests with the trustee unless one of the two exceptions outlined in BIA ss.67(1)(c)(i) or (ii) exist. Currently, section 118.2 of the ITA [s. 118.3?] does not indicate that the DTC [disability tax credit] is not subject to the operation of the BIA. Therefore, if it can be determined that the DTC relates to the year of bankruptcy <UNDER>or a prior year</UNDER>, it will vest with the trustee. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>135. With respect to Mr. Bennett, <UNDER>nowhere</UNDER> in section 67(1)(c), as it now reads, does it refer to refunds owing to the bankrupt in respect of years prior to the date of bankruptcy. Furthermore, if the refund is &ldquo;property&rdquo; and one of the other exceptions in section 67(1)(a) or (b) applies because, for example, all or part of it is exempt, then we submit those provisions would still apply. What is also not considered by Mr. Bennett or Registrar Harrison is whether sub-paragraph 67(1)(c)(i) [&ldquo;is not subject to the operation of this Act&rdquo;] could exclude from &ldquo;property&rdquo; certain refunds, even in the year of bankruptcy, which are either exempt as wages or not subject to the operation of the Act because they are akin to an award for pain and suffering, that is, amounts payable only by reason of the physical or mental disability of a person.</P>
<P>136. In the result, Registrar Harrison concluded that the law with regard to all income tax refunds, including DTC's, was clarified by the amendments to section 67 and, in respect of assignments filed after July 7<SUP>th</SUP>, 2008, all such refunds, including all pre-bankruptcy personal tax refunds, were &ldquo;property&rdquo; available for creditors.</P>
<P>137. With respect, we think that Registrar Harrison's failure to consider that the amendment to section 67(1)(c) only specifically addressed tax refunds payable &ldquo;in respect of the year of bankruptcy and his failure to consider the possibility that such property can still be &ldquo;wages&rdquo;, and subject to any provincial exemptions for wages, or that such refund could otherwise &ldquo;not be subject to the operation of the Act&rdquo;, makes this decision of limited value.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Pain and Suffering Cases</UNDER></TI>
<P>138. We now turn to a brief review of the cases which address damages arising from physical or mental suffering of the debtor. The leading case is <CASEREF><SOC>Re: Hollister</SOC><CITE>[1926] 7 CBR 629</CITE></CASEREF>, which appears at <BOLD>Part 2 TAB 24,</BOLD> a decision of Mr. Justice Fisher of what was then the Ontario Supreme Court. He held that monies recovered by an undischarged debtor for personal injuries sustained by him was not &ldquo;property&rdquo; divisible among his creditors under the <EM>Bankruptcy Act</EM>. We have previously quoted his often-cited statement of this well-known principle in our review of <EM>Neufeld</EM> above.</P>
<P>139. Other cases frequently cited, and attached to <BOLD>Part 2</BOLD>, are the following:
<P1>(a) <CASEREF><SOC>Eggen v. Grayson</SOC><YEAR>1956</YEAR><CITE>36 CBR 72</CITE></CASEREF>, a decision of Mr. Justice Boyd McBride of the Alberta Supreme Court&mdash;<BOLD>TAB 25</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(b) <CASEREF><SOC>Re Ritenberg</SOC><CITE>[1961] AJ No. 58</CITE></CASEREF>, a decision of Mr. Justice Riley of the Alberta Supreme Court&mdash;<BOLD>TAB 26</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(c) <CASEREF><SOC>Holley v. Gifford Smith Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1986</YEAR><CITE>O.J. No. 165</CITE><COURTJUR>Ontario C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>&mdash;<BOLD>TAB 27</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(d) <CASEREF><SOC>Re Conforti</SOC><CITE>[2015] O.J. No. 1986</CITE><COURTJUR>Ontario C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>&mdash;<BOLD>TAB 28</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(e) <CASEREF><SOC>Re: Rice</SOC><YEAR>2016</YEAR><CITE>NBQB 134</CITE></CASEREF>, a decision of Deputy Registrar Evans of the New Brunswick Court of Queen's Bench&mdash;<BOLD>TAB 29</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>140. <EM>Eggen</EM> was a case where the debtor's action was based on malicious prosecution and sought damages for pain, humiliation and injury to his reputation. In <EM>Ritenberg</EM>, the debtor was involved in a motor vehicle accident and sought damages for personal injuries and pain and suffering. Both cases referred with approval to <EM>Hollister</EM> and reached the conclusion such claims and damages were not &ldquo;property&rdquo; available to creditors.</P>
<P>141. In <CASEREF><SOC>Holley v. Gifford Smith Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, the Ontario Court of Appeal considered a situation where a bankrupt's action for wrongful dismissal vested as property in the trustee. The action included a claim for damages for mental distress. The court decided that damages for mental distress were personal to the bankrupt and &ldquo;it is not the policy of the law to convert into money for the creditors the mental or physical anguish of the debtor&rdquo;.</P>
<P>142. In<EM>Conforti</EM>, the Ontario Court of Appeal considered various heads of compensation received by a bankrupt arising from a motor vehicle accident. The bankrupt was permanently disabled and unable to continue to work. He received income assistance, a lump sum settlement of statutory accident benefits and various amounts of damages in settlement of his personal injury claim. The Court of Appeal concluded that damages for future care and housekeeping should not be included as &ldquo;income&rdquo; of the bankrupt and were not otherwise available to the trustee. The court held such amounts were damages that were personal to the appellant and bore a close relationship to damages on account of pain and suffering, and noted there was extensive support for the proposition that damages for pain and suffering do not fall under sections 67 or 68 of the BIA.</P>
<P>143. In <CASEREF><SOC>Re Rice</SOC></CASEREF>, the bankrupt had received a lump sum payment from the New Brunswick version of the Workers' Compensation Board. The court referred to <EM>Ritenberg, Holley</EM> and <EM>Conforti</EM>. Registrar Evans then observed that New Brunswick courts have recognized common law damage awards for lost opportunity arising from personal injuries and also noted that the lump sum received from Ms. Rice was statutorily characterized by the New Brunswick <EM>Workers' Compensation Act</EM> as a loss of opportunity for permanent physical impairment. This was a statutory method of compensation for her physical loss arising from a workplace injury. The court found this loss was personal in nature to Ms. Rice and, accordingly, it was not an asset for purposes of the BIA. &ldquo;To hold otherwise would, in my view, convert into money for the creditors the physical anguish of the debtor thereby contravening the stated policy of the law.&rdquo; (paragraph 20)</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VII">VII. <UNDER>CONCLUSIONS</UNDER></TI>
<P>144. Having considered the legislative history of sections 67 and 68 of the BIA, the policies and objectives of the BIA which include the financial rehabilitation of the bankrupt, and the decided cases and, in particular, <EM>Marzetti, Landry, Hynes, Cole, Bowerbank-Buckley</EM> and <EM>Ford</EM>, and the &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo; cases beginning with <EM>Hollister</EM>, we have reached the following conclusions:</P>
<P>(1) An income tax refund which results from claiming a disability tax credit is &ldquo;income&rdquo;.</P>
<P>(2) If a disability tax credit was claimed in relation to a person who is financially dependant on the bankrupt, the refund payable to the bankrupt is not held in trust by the bankrupt for the disabled dependant. There is no statutory deemed trust applicable to refunds arising from disability tax credits, nor is there a &ldquo;true&rdquo; trust created. It is the bankrupt's asset.</P>
<P>(3) It is the character of the asset and not the accident of timing which determines whether or not the refund is subject to the provisions of the BIA. Language such as &ldquo;in respect of&rdquo; the year of bankruptcy or &ldquo;earned&rdquo; during the period of bankruptcy is a clear indication to us that it is the taxation year to which the refund relates that is relevant, even if the refunds were not actually paid until after the date of discharge.</P>
<P>(4) Section 68 of the BIA as it now reads is applicable only to &ldquo;total income&rdquo; which is <UNDER>earned</UNDER> OR <UNDER>received</UNDER> by the bankrupt between the date of the bankruptcy and the date of the bankrupt's discharge. The &lsquo;or&rdquo; is important. If an income tax refund becomes payable to the bankrupt after his or her discharge but pertains to (was <UNDER>earned</UNDER> during) the period of bankruptcy, then section 68 applies, unless it is a refund for the post-bankruptcy portion of the year of bankruptcy, in which case section 67(1)(c) applies. Likewise, if a pre-bankruptcy income tax refund was <UNDER>received</UNDER> during bankruptcy, section 68 applies.</P>
<P>(5) With respect to &ldquo;total income&rdquo; [income tax refunds] earned or received by the bankrupt during the period of his or her bankruptcy, the provincial exemptions applicable to wages do not apply, because subsection 68(2)(a), which defines &ldquo;total income&rdquo;, specifically states &ldquo;despite paragraphs 67(1)(b) and (b.3)&rdquo;. However, under section 68, it would be open to a bankrupt to argue that all or most of these refunds should be left in his or her hands given their family situation and the needs of their disabled dependant.</P>
<P>(6) Although the 2009 amendment to section 68 has effectively made section 68 a &ldquo;complete code&rdquo; only with respect to revenues earned or received during the period of bankruptcy, it still does not change the character of the asset. An income tax refund payable by reason of a disability tax credit claim is still &ldquo;income&rdquo;. Accordingly, the &ldquo;pre-amendment&rdquo; situation described in <EM>Marzetti</EM>, and based on the reasoning in <CASEREF><SOC>Industrial Acceptance Corp. v. Lalonde</SOC></CASEREF>, applies to income tax refunds which have retained their character as &ldquo;wages&rdquo; for the period prior to the date of bankruptcy and were either paid and still held by the bankrupt at the date of bankruptcy or received sometime after the date of discharge, i.e. they are not &ldquo;received&rdquo; during the bankruptcy. To the extent they are not caught by section 68, these pre-bankruptcy refunds now vest in the trustee by reason of sections 67 and 71 of the BIA, but the provincial exemptions apply. In other words, the vesting of these refunds in the trustee does not preclude or overcome the application of provincial exemption laws. The trustee is unable to retain more than the exigible piece; the balance of these pre-bankruptcy refunds must be returned to the bankrupt as exempt property. Put another way, given the 2009 amendment to section 68, the &ldquo;exemption&rdquo; approach described in <EM>Ramgotra</EM>, and discussed in the Klotz article, is now the law as far as pre-bankruptcy earnings or wages not &ldquo;received&rdquo; during bankruptcy are concerned.</P>
<P>(7) Under Alberta law, the exemptions applicable to wages are contained in section 81 of the <EM>Civil Enforcement Act</EM> and sections 39 to 40 of the <EM>Civil Enforcement Regulation</EM>, copies of which are attached to <BOLD>Part 1, TAB R and TAB S.</BOLD> The employment earnings exemption is calculated on a monthly basis. The actual employment earnings exemption is the minimum exemption [$800 plus $200 per dependant] plus one-half of the amount by which the debtor's net pay exceeds the minimum exemption up to the maximum exemption [$2,400 plus $200 per dependant]. Therefore, assuming these pre-bankruptcy refunds were paid after the date of discharge, we think it would be necessary for the trustee to assess the bankrupt's average monthly income during the pre-bankruptcy years for which these tax refunds were received and, treating the refunds received as the last dollars earned, calculate what portion of the refund is exigible and payable to the trustee, and what portion should remain in the bankrupt's hands as exempt. Furthermore, with respect to &ldquo;wages&rdquo; [income tax refunds] attributable to the pre-bankruptcy years and not &ldquo;received&rdquo; during bankruptcy, we think there is an argument that section 67(1)(b) should be not limited to statutory exemptions. There are other grounds on which such income may be exempt from execution or seizure &ldquo;under any laws applicable in the province&rdquo;. Following the &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo; cases, it could be argued that none of these pre-bankruptcy refunds should be available to the trustee, because they are similar, in policy and purpose, to amounts paid to alleviate pain and suffering such as housekeeping or personal care. In the case at bar, the only reason the disability tax credits were available, and the only reason these additional income tax refunds were generated, is because of the disability of the bankrupt's child. If her child was not disabled, there would be no credits and no refunds, and no additional assets available to the trustee. If it is not the policy of the law to convert into money for creditors the mental or physical anguish of a debtor, how could it be the policy of the law to convert into money for a parent's creditors the mental or physical anguish of her child?</P>
<P>(8) As to the refund owing to the bankrupt in respect of the year of bankruptcy, section 67(1)(c) now includes the refund <UNDER>for that year only</UNDER> as &ldquo;property&rdquo;. However, the exception to this provision contained in subsection 67(1)(c)(i) [&ldquo;except the portion that is not subject to the operation of this Act&rdquo;], must be given some meaning. We agree there is nothing in the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> which would exempt refunds arising from disability tax credits. However, we do not think this is the end of the analysis. The income tax refund received for the year of bankruptcy is still &ldquo;income&rdquo; and at least the exemptions under provincial law should apply and, as discussed above, those could include both statutory exemptions and assets not available to creditors as a matter of public policy.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED at Calgary, Alberta, this 24th day of November, 2017.</P>
<P>MILES DAVISON LLP, as Amicus Curiae</P>
<P>Per: &ellip35;</P>
<P>Susan L. Robinson Burns, Q.C.</P></BLOCK2>
