<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">I. Introduction and Issues</TI>
<P>1. On October 3, 2017, the Court appointed Miles Davison LLP as <EM>amicus curiae</EM> (the &ldquo;Amicus&rdquo;) for the purpose of preparing and making submissions to the Court at a special application before a Registrar regarding,
<QUOTE><P>the application of principles of law and equity, including without limitation, the interpretation and application of current statutory provisions, to the facts and circumstances pertaining to the disability tax credits claimed by the bankrupt by reason of her child's disability, and the fund of $20,339.82 (the &ldquo;Fund&rdquo;) arising therefrom, which Fund is presently held in trust by the Trustee, for the purpose of deciding the person or persons entitled to such Fund or portions thereof.</P></QUOTE>
(the &ldquo;Directions&rdquo;)</P>
<P>2. The Amicus's brief states that &ldquo;Registrar Prowse considered it necessary and appropriate that the legal issues raised in this matter be researched and briefed by an impartial legal advisor for the assistance of this Honourable Court.&rdquo; And, in that respect, the Amicus produced a lengthy brief summarizing the relevant facts, analyzing the relevant legislation and analyzing a number of cases that dealt with disability tax credit (&ldquo;DTC&rdquo;) income tax refunds.</P>
<P>3. The Alberta Association of Insolvency and Restructuring Professionals (&ldquo;AAIRP&rdquo;), the professional association of Licensed Insolvency Trustees (&ldquo;Trustees&rdquo;) in Alberta applied to appear as intervenor, file its own brief and make its own submissions because:
<P1>a. its members will be affected by the decision facing the Court;</P1>
<P1>b. it has special expertise and insight to bring to the issues facing the Court; and</P1>
<P1>c. the Trustee has no resources in the Estate to fund representation, so the interests of Trustees, generally, would not be fully protected without the involvement of the AAIRP as intervenor.</P1></P>
<P>4. On December 8, 2017, AAIRP was granted status as intervenor.</P>
<P>5. The Amicus, in accordance with the Directions, considered who, as between the Trustee and Ms. Chomistek, was entitled to all or part of the Fund and concluded that Ms. Chomistek was.</P>
<P>6. Despite the Amicus setting out the current state of the law, and its agreement with the reasoning in <EM>Hynes, Cole</EM> and <EM>Ford</EM>, the Amicus reached its conclusions using a different type of analysis of the pre-bankruptcy DTC income tax refunds and two legal positions not supported by the current state of the law, namely: (a) the applicability of provincial wage exemptions and (b) the relevance of the &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo; cases.</P>
<P>7. Notwithstanding that AAIRP disagrees with the Amicus' conclusions, it does agree with the Amicus that:
<P1>a. An income tax refund is an asset of a bankrupt;</P1>
<P1>b. The tax refund for the year of bankruptcy is property of the bankrupt that vests with the Trustee per s. 67(1)(c) of the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM> (the &ldquo;BIA&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>c. In this specific case, the pre-bankruptcy income tax refunds arising from the DTCs are &ldquo;income&rdquo; as it is derived from the bankrupt's employment&mdash;wages;</P1>
<P1>d. Section 68 of the BIA applies to pre-bankruptcy income tax refunds received during bankruptcy and post-bankruptcy income tax refunds (other than the year of the bankruptcy) payable to the bankrupt while in bankruptcy; and</P1>
<P1>e. The DTC claimed by a bankrupt in respect of a dependent is the bankrupt's asset and not held in trust for the disabled dependent.</P1></P>
<P>8. AAlRP's role in this matter is to ensure that the proper analysis is used so that Trustees can discharge their duties under the BIA, namely s. 68, and not have to consider unnecessary issues.</P>
<P>9. This brief utilizes the Amicus' cases where applicable and does not re-cite them herein unless quoting a specific passage.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">II. The Tax Refund for the Year of Bankruptcy</TI>
<P>10. Ms. Chomistek received an income tax refund in respect of tax years 2006 to 2013 (the year of bankruptcy) totaling $20,339.82. A table breaking down the tax refund per tax year is located at paragraph 13 of the Amicus' brief.</P>
<P>11. Of that amount, $2,879.36 relates to the pre- and post- bankruptcy tax returns filed in respect of the year of bankruptcy, 2013. The remaining $17,460.46 is for the tax years 2006 to 2012, the pre-bankruptcy period.</P>
<P>12. Section 67(1)(c) states that &ldquo;any refund owing to the bankrupt under the Income Tax Act in respect of the calendar year&mdash;or the fiscal year of the bankrupt if different from the calendar year&mdash;in which the bankrupt became a bankrupt&rdquo; is property of the bankrupt and divisible among her creditors. There are two exceptions to the rule pertaining to the tax refund issued for the year of bankruptcy: (a) that portion that is not subject to the operation of the BIA; and (b) money captured by a garnishee summons issued under the <EM>Family Orders and Agreements Enforcement Assistance Act</EM>.</P>
<P>13. In this case, Ms. Chomistek's 2013 income tax refunds fall within s.67(1)(c) and vest in the Trustee. Neither of the exceptions apply.</P>
<P>14. This then leaves the pre-bankruptcy tax refunds arising from the DTCs. AAlRP's analysis of this issue starts with a review of the different ways that Courts have addressed this issue. After which, this Brief will consider the 2 issues in which AAlRP's analysis is different than the Amicus and the recommended practice for Trustees to handle these types of situations going forward.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">III. Case Analysis re Bankrupt's Pre-Bankruptcy DTC Income Tax Refunds</TI>
<P>15. Per Justice lacobucci at the Supreme Court of Canada (&ldquo;SCC&rdquo;) and Justice Major at the Alberta Court of Appeal, tax refunds can be generated from a number of sources of income, including wages. Whether tax refunds can be characterized as wages, &ldquo;depends on the nature of the refund&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Marzetti v. Marzetti</SOC><CITE>[1994] 2 SCR 765</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Marzetti</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 78 to 80, Part 2, Tab 1 of the Amicus' Brief.</P1></P>
<P>16. Just as lacobucci J. did in <EM>Marzetti</EM>, we accept that Ms. Chomistek's income tax refunds for the tax years 2006 to 2012, the pre-bankruptcy period, arose from her wages.</P>
<P>17. How should Ms. Chomistek's pre-bankruptcy DTC income tax refunds be treated? The Amicus' states that there is no consistent conclusion that can be reached from the reported cases which have considered DTC income tax refunds and while that may be true, the decisions reached by the various courts in matters of DTCs and <EM>other pre-bankruptcy earnings</EM>, and their reasoning, can be separated into a few different categories.</P>
<P>18. Our analysis starts with the 3 categories identified in Robert A. Klotz's paper, &ldquo;Who Gets the Bankrupt's Pre-Bankruptcy Earnings?&rdquo; (&ldquo;Klotz&rdquo;) produced at Part 2, Tab 12 of the Amicus' brief: (a) the &ldquo;exemption&rdquo; approach; (b) the &ldquo;vesting&rdquo; approach; and (c) the &ldquo;s. 68&rdquo; approach.
<QUOTE><P>What makes this topic confusing is the utilization by the courts, in different, cases, of three separate conceptual treatments of pre-bankruptcy earnings.</P></QUOTE>
The version of Mr. Klotz's paper produced in the Amicus' brief has some formatting and typographical errors making it difficult to ascertain the 3 approaches. A clean version from Mr. Klotz's website is attached at <BOLD>TAB 1</BOLD> of this brief.</P>
<P>19. Building from the foundation of Mr. Klotz's approaches, I have identified 2 other categories: (d) the &ldquo;pre-67/post-68&rdquo; approach; and (e) the &ldquo;equitable&rdquo; approach. Attached as Schedules &ldquo;A&rdquo;, &ldquo;B&rdquo;, &ldquo;C&rdquo;, &ldquo;D&rdquo; and &ldquo;E&rdquo; to this Brief, I have categorized those cases listed in Mr. Klotz's paper, the cases provided by the Amicus, cases relied on within the Amicus' cases and a few cases that had not been previously considered.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>The &ldquo;Exemption&rdquo; Approach</UNDER></TI>
<P>20. Mr. Klotz's first approach is the &ldquo;Exemption&rdquo; Approach and the application of provincial exemption laws to analyze the priority issues affecting funds caught in a priority dispute between a bankruptcy and spousal or child support garnishments and paid into Court. In these cases, the Trustee had priority over the non-exempt portion and the wife's garnishment for support payments took priority over the remaining exempt amounts.</P>
<P>21. These cases and their reasoning are not applicable to DTC income tax refund cases, so I do not find the &ldquo;exemption&rdquo; approach relevant to Ms. Chomistek.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>The &ldquo;Vesting&rdquo; Approach</UNDER></TI>
<P>22. The second approach, the &ldquo;Vesting&rdquo; Approach, is the line of authority that <EM>pre-bankruptcy</EM> earnings, and anything derived therefrom, accrue to the Trustee without limitation.
<QUOTE><P>These cases are based on the view that BIA s. 68 applies only to post-bankruptcy wages, and that consequently pre-bankruptcy wages constitute property of the bankrupt estate, vesting entirely in the trustee, for distribution among creditors. <EM>The rationale for this view is that the pre-bankruptcy wages ought to accrue to the creditors who presumably went unpaid, or whose debts were presumably increased, as a result of the inability of the debtor to access those wages before the bankruptcy</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Klotz at p.2</P1></P>
<P>23. Mr. Klotz goes on to say that,
<QUOTE><P>The technical justification for this view is that s. 68 applies by its terms to the revenue of the &ldquo;bankrupt&rdquo;&mdash;since the status of &ldquo;bankrupt&rdquo; begins only upon the date of bankruptcy, the section is applicable only for the period following that date, when there is indeed a bankrupt.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>24. As you can see from Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;, this was an approach used <EM>pre-Marzetti</EM> based on the strict wording of s. 68 at the time, and then by a few cases post-<EM>Marzetti</EM> on the basis that <EM>Marzetti</EM> stood for the position that s. 68 only applied to post-bankruptcy revenue.</P>
<P>25. With specific reference to DTC income tax refund cases, we find that the majority of courts west of Ontario have applied this approach notwithstanding the wording of s. 68 at the time of those decisions. I believe the reasoning for this line of DTC income tax refund cases traces back to 1997 when <CASEREF><SOC>Marzetti and Sobieski</SOC><YEAR>1997</YEAR><CITE>45 C.B.R. (32) 272</CITE><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><YEAR>1997</YEAR><CITE>2 C.B.R. (4th) 70</CITE><COURTJUR>Man. Q.B.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Sobieski</EM>&rdquo;) had already been decided but before the Supreme Court of Canada rendered its decision in <EM>Wallace</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>I note that the Registrar's decision in <EM>Sobieski</EM> was rendered on January 15, 1997 and the Justice's decision on appeal was rendered October 10, 1997. Interestingly, <EM>Wallace</EM>, also arising from Manitoba, was decided October 30, 1997 by the Supreme Court of Canada. I suspect that because it was dealing with a pre-bankruptcy wrongful dismissal claim, and not a disability tax credit income tax refund, the Manitoba courts hearing <EM>Sobieski</EM> did not consider that <EM>Wallace</EM> may have had an impact on their decisions.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. My concern regarding the &ldquo;vesting&rdquo; approach cases is that these cases either focus on whether the DTCs were the property of the bankrupt or the disabled person<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ford</EM> at para. 30. <EM>Bolz, Sobieski, Nixon, Neufeld</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> or they do not appear to consider the wording of section 68 and <EM>Marzetti, Wallace</EM> and <EM>Landry</EM> (where applicable)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Nixon, Henderson, Bolz, Phillips and Gabrielle</EM></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>. Interestingly, the Courts in <CASEREF><SOC>Re Potter</SOC><CITE>2010 MBQB 36</CITE><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>2010 MBQB 77</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Potter</EM>&rdquo;) did consider s. 68 but then made their decision using the &ldquo;vesting&rdquo; approach.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>I note that <EM>Potter</EM> is another decision on disability tax credit refunds arising out of Manitoba leaving one to wonder if the Courts deferred to the <EM>Sobieski</EM> decision because it came from their own Court.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>27. In <CASEREF><SOC>Re Byrne</SOC></CASEREF>, Registrar Funduk describes the bankruptcy court's move away from the &ldquo;vesting approach&rdquo;,
<QUOTE><P>Prior to 1997 bankruptcy courts used provincial exemptions law for exemptions for income. The 1997 change eliminates that and creates a uniform standard <UNDER>which applies regardless of the sources of income</UNDER>. <EM>Houlden &amp; Morawetz, Bankruptcy &amp; Insolvency Act</EM> (The 2003 Annotated) correctly point out that s. 68 now avoids trying to classify income, p. 355. Section 68(1) says &ldquo;total income&rdquo; and s.-s.(2) says &ldquo;total income&rdquo; includes &ldquo;all revenues of a bankrupt of whatever nature and source&rdquo;.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Re Byrne</SOC><CITE>2003 ABQB 216 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>15</PARANUM></CASEREF> at <BOLD>TAB 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. Mr. Klotz's paper also concludes that the &ldquo;vesting&rdquo; approach is &ldquo;no longer defensible, despite its lengthy pedigree&rdquo;.</P>
<P>29. For the reasons above and those that follow, we do not prescribe to using the &ldquo;vesting&rdquo; approach in dealing with Ms. Chomistek's pre-bankruptcy income tax refunds.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>The &ldquo;Section 68&rdquo; Approach</UNDER></TI>
<P>30. The third and final approach identified by Mr. Klotz is the &ldquo;Section 68&rdquo; approach which is characterized by a &ldquo;liberal and purposive interpretation&rdquo; of s. 68 of the BIA, extending its application to the pre-bankruptcy period. Mr. Klotz states that this line of authority arises from a trilogy of Supreme Court of Canada cases: <EM>Marzetti, Ramgotra</EM> and <EM>Wallace</EM>. While I agree that this approach does arise from a trilogy of cases, I believe the appropriate trilogy is <EM>Marzetti, Wallace</EM> and <EM>Landry</EM>, not <EM>Ramgotra</EM>. <EM>Ramgotra</EM> was a case about whether a transfer of funds in a non-exempt asset to an exempt asset could be void against the Trustee as a settlement. It was not about pre-bankruptcy earnings as Mr. Klotz's paper or the Amicus' brief suggests.</P>
<P>31. Both <EM>Marzetti</EM> and <EM>Wallace</EM> involve post-bankruptcy, not pre-bankruptcy, income. But, the Supreme Court's reasoning in <EM>Wallace</EM> suggests that the distinction is irrelevant. <EM>Wallace</EM> retained his right to sue for severance &ldquo;not because of the tinning of the acquisition of such property, but rather, because of the nature of the property in question.&rdquo; If property has the character of wages, its status in bankruptcy is not dependent upon when the claim arose. <EM>Wallace's</EM> claim was after-acquired property but it derived from wages and thus fell within s. 68.
<QUOTE><P>It is the character of the asset, not the accident of timing, that determines whether or not it falls into the bankrupt estate.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Wallace</EM>, at para. 69, at Part 2, Tab 3 of the Amicus' Brief.</P1></P>
<P>32. It is from these cases that the principle that s. 68 of the BIA is a complete code with respect to wages arises,
<QUOTE><P>In my view, the reasoning in <EM>Marzetti</EM> and <EM>Wallace</EM> that led to the conclusion that s. 68 was a complete code with respect to wages applies equally to this new section. The current provision applies to the &ldquo;total income&rdquo; of the bankrupt and, as such, is even wider than the earlier reference to &ldquo;salary, wages and other remuneration&rdquo;; the provision expressly excludes the application of s. 67(1)(b); its purpose is no different than that described in <EM>Marzetti</EM> (except that applications to the court now appear to be limited to those cases where the issue cannot be otherwise resolved); and the jurisprudential principles reviewed by the Supreme Court in <EM>Marzetti</EM> are equally relevant.</P>
<P>I therefore conclude that s. 67 is superseded by the provisions of the current s. 68 in so far as the &ldquo;total income&rdquo; of the bankrupt is concerned. It follows that, as in <EM>Wallace</EM>, Landry's claim against her former employer and any consequent award relating to lost wages do not automatically vest in the trustee under ss. 67 and 71. Resort can only be had to s. 68 for payment of any portion thereof to the estate of the bankrupt.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Re Landry</SOC></CASEREF>, para. 30 to 31 at Part 2, Tab 2 of the Amicus' Brief.</P1></P>
<P>33. Registrar Creegan in <EM>Ford</EM> summarizes the &ldquo;s. 68&rdquo; approach as follows,
<QUOTE><P>... if the funds in question are &ldquo;salary, wages or other remuneration&rdquo; under the old wording of s. 68 or are part of &ldquo;total income&rdquo; including &ldquo;all revenue of a bankrupt of whatever nature or source&rdquo; under the present wording of s. 68 earned or in some other way crystalized during the bankruptcy period and received during the bankruptcy or after discharge, they are to be distributed under s. 68. This follows clearly from <EM>Marzetti</EM>. It further follows from <EM>Landry</EM> that this applies also to such funds earned or crystalized before assignment, but not received until after assignment into bankruptcy.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Re Ford</SOC></CASEREF> at para. 37, at Part 2, Tab 20 of the Amicus' Brief.</P1></P>
<P>34. The Amicus found nothing wrong in the analysis or the courts in <EM>Hynes</EM> (&ldquo;we think he was entirely correct&rdquo;), <EM>Cole</EM> and <EM>Ford</EM> (&ldquo;we think this decision was very well reasoned&rdquo;) and how they applied the s. 68 approach, yet the Amicus did not utilize the s. 68 approach or those Courts' analysis in coming to its conclusions.</P>
<P>35. Further, the Amicus agreed with the majority of Registrar Diamond's analysis in <EM>Bowerbank-Buckley</EM>, but disagreed with his misinterpretation of <EM>Landry</EM> and his decision not to apply s.68 (&ldquo;Registrar Diamond then, in our respectful view, made something of a hard left turn and, in doing so, misapplied the principles in <EM>Landry</EM>&rdquo;). The Amicus made the same &ldquo;hard left turn&rdquo; away from the s. 68 approach that it was otherwise in agreement with, in its own conclusions.</P>
<P>36. AAIRP submits that the s. 68 approach is the current state of the law and should be applied to Ms. Chomistek's pre-bankruptcy DTC income tax returns. It is submitted that the Amicus' brief was lending to his same conclusion until it began to refer to &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo; cases, provincial wage exemptions and <EM>Ramgotra</EM>.</P>
<BLOCK4><TI>Why Ramgotra is not a Section 68 Case (and not a Wages/Earnings Case)</TI>
<P>37. Mr. Klotz's paper makes it sound like the SCC in Ramgotra gave great consideration to s. 68 in <EM>Ramgotra</EM>, which is just not true. <EM>Ramgotra</EM> was a case about a doctor in Saskatchewan who transferred money in a non-exempt asset, (his RRSPs were not exempt at the time) to an exempt asset, (RRIFs naming his wife as the beneficiary) 2 years before his made his assignment into bankruptcy and whether this was a &ldquo;settlement&rdquo; and void against the Trustee. RRSPs were an asset that fell within s. 67&mdash;they were not earnings or wages. And, they certainly were not pre-bankruptcy wages as we are dealing with in this matter.</P>
<P>38. I believe that Mr. Klotz and the Amicus are both relying on para. 60 of <EM>Ramgotra</EM>, the only paragraph of the 43 pages of <EM>Ramgotra</EM> that referenced s. 68 of the BIA, and it states,
<QUOTE><P>After-acquired property is also dealt with in s. 68, which constitutes a complete code in respect of a bankrupt's salary, wages or other remuneration. The provision stipulates that after-acquired remuneration will not pass to and vest in the trustee unless the trustee intervenes by applying for a court order directing the payment of the remuneration (or a portion of it) to the trustee.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>39. In my opinion, para. 60 of <EM>Ramgotra</EM> falls far below a clear statement that s. 68 was limited to or <UNDER>only</UNDER> applied to post-bankruptcy salary, wages and other remuneration <UNDER>and not</UNDER> pre-bankruptcy wages. Instead, I read para. 60 as the Court explaining how provincial exemptions in property apply to an asset that otherwise vests in the Trustee under s. 67 but provincial exemptions do not apply if salary, wages and other remuneration which fall under s. 68 because s. 68 is a complete code.</P>
<P>40. In any event, as <EM>Ramgotra</EM> was not dealing with s. 68 of the BIA, para. 47 can also be taken as <EM>obiter dicta</EM>. Courts generally exclude <EM>Ramgotra</EM> from analysis of pre-bankruptcy wages as can be seen by the <EM>Wallace</EM> decision, one year after <EM>Ramgotra</EM>, and the <EM>Landry</EM> decision which both supported the SCC's reasoning in <EM>Marzetti</EM>.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI><UNDER>The &ldquo;Pre-67/Post-68&rdquo; Approach</UNDER></TI>
<P>41. The next two approaches, the &ldquo;Pre-67/Post-68&rdquo; Approach and the &ldquo;Equitable&rdquo; Approach are categories not identified by Mr. Klotz, not used by Courts very often and often distinguished by other courts. However, they are both approaches that the Amicus gives weight to in reaching its conclusions.</P>
<P>42. If one were to take the position that <EM>Ramgotra</EM> was a relevant case notwithstanding that it deals with a settlement issue over an otherwise non-exempt asset and not earnings or wages, pre-bankruptcy or otherwise, then <EM>Ramgotra</EM> would fall within the &ldquo;pre-67/post-68&rdquo; approach.</P>
<P>43. According to Mr. Klotz and the Amicus, s. 68 does not apply to pre-bankruptcy wages so all pre-bankruptcy wages vest in the Trustee under s. 67. If s. 67 applies, then so too do provincial wage exemptions. Thus, the Trustee is unable to retain more than the non-exempt portion&mdash;the exempt portion is returned to the bankrupt. This is really nothing more than the application of the vesting approach to pre-bankruptcy wages&mdash;something that both Registrar Funduk and Mr. Klotz say no longer applies.</P>
<P>44. Based on my review, this &ldquo;pre-67/post-68&rdquo; approach taken by the SCC in <EM>Ramgotra</EM> in 1996 was short-lived as in 1997, the SCC rendered its decision in <EM>Wallace</EM> which again reiterated the application of s. 68 to both pre- and post-bankruptcy income.</P>
<P>45. I am only aware of one DTC income tax refund decision that follows the &ldquo;pre-67/post-68&rdquo; approach, <EM>Bolz</EM>, which the Amicus points out is flawed by how it failed to characterize the DTC income tax refund as earnings or wages, in accordance with <EM>Marzetti</EM>.</P>
<P>46. While the Amicus relies on <EM>Ramgotra</EM> in reaching its conclusion, I note a conflict between conclusions 4 and 6 on page 38 of the Amicus' brief. On one hand (conclusion 4), the Amicus states, and I agree, that section 68 of the BIA applies to &ldquo;total income&rdquo; which is &ldquo;earned OR received&rdquo; by the bankrupt between the date of the bankruptcy and the date of the bankrupt's discharge. Then, on the other hand (conclusion 6), the Amicus states that the law as far as pre-bankruptcy earnings &ldquo;not received&rdquo; during bankruptcy is that <EM>Ramgotra</EM> applies. This fails to take into account the &ldquo;earned&rdquo; aspect of s. 68 that the Amicus reached at conclusion 4.</P>
<P>47. Section 68 is a complete code and does not utilize provincial wage exemptions, but as you will see below, built into it is the ability of a Trustee or the Court to give consideration to a bankrupt's personal and family situation.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI><UNDER>The &ldquo;Equitable&rdquo; Approach</UNDER></TI>
<P>48. Finally, we have the &ldquo;equitable&rdquo; approach that was used in <EM>Neufeld</EM>. In my opinion, this was a result-driven decision. The Court found a trust so that the bankrupt, the recipient of the refunds, was not the owner of the refunds but instead only holding the refunds for the benefit of the disabled dependant.</P>
<P>49. As stated by Registrar Creegan in <EM>Ford</EM>, &ldquo;[t]he decision has been criticized and the trust analysis is generally not accepted.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ford</EM> at para. 29 at Part 2, TAB 20 of the Amicus' Brief.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>50. I did not see similar reasoning used with respect to any other DTC income tax refund cases and submit that the &ldquo;equitable&rdquo; approach is not applicable today. Furthermore, such reasoning is unnecessary given the fact that s. 68 is a complete code and provides consideration of a bankrupt's personal and family situation.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">IV. Procedure to be Applied</TI>
<P>51. Using the s. 68 approach to analyze Ms. Chomistek's pre-bankruptcy DTC income tax refunds, we take the following steps (remembering that the tax refunds of $2,879.36 for the year of bankruptcy vest in the Trustee per s.67(1)(c)):
<P1>a. First, we characterize the asset. In this specific case, the pre-bankruptcy income tax refunds arising from the DTC are &ldquo;income&rdquo; as they are derived from the bankrupt's employment&mdash;wages. And, in this case, the amount at issue totals $17,460.46.</P1>
<P1>b. Then, s. 68 dictates that:
<P2>i. the Trustee &ldquo;having regard to [the Superintendent Guidelines] and to the personal and family situation of the bankrupt, determines whether the bankrupt has surplus income.&rdquo; In this case, Ms. Chomistek received an increase in income (lump sum payment of pre-bankruptcy income) as provided at Example 5 of Directive No. 11R2-2017, Surplus Income.
<P3>Office of the Superintendent of Bankruptcy Canada&mdash;Directive No. 11R2-2017, Surplus Income at <BOLD>TAB 3.</BOLD></P3></P2>
I see little difference between a bankrupt receiving a lump sum payment for lost wages (like in <EM>Landry</EM>) and a bankrupt receiving income tax refunds for pre-bankruptcy tax returns where the income being refunded was derived from the bankrupt's wages.
<P2>ii. In 2017, the Superintendent's Standard for a family of 3 was $3,246.00, so a calculation based on the bankrupt's monthly income of $3,156.28 would ordinarily result in $16,652.98 of the pre-bankruptcy income tax refunds to accrue to the estate, as follows:
