<P2>iii. The Trustee's determination would be subject to the Official Receiver's recommendation;</P2>
<P2>iv. If the Trustee and the bankrupt do not agree with the amount that the bankrupt would be required to pay, the Trustee can request mediation (similarly a Creditor can as well); and</P2>
<P2>v. The Trustee can make an application to the Court to have the Court fix the amount that the bankrupt is required to pay to the Estate for surplus income. In determining whether the bankrupt has surplus income and how much they shall pay to their estate, the Court will also have regard to the Superintendent Guidelines and to the personal and family situation of the bankrupt.</P2></P1></P>
<P>52. Based on the Superintendent Guideline surplus income calculation above, Ms. Chomistek would be entitled to receive $807.48, and the remaining $16,652.98 of pre-bankruptcy earnings Would be payable to the Estate.</P>
<P>53. Of course, the above calculation does not take into account the personal and family situation of the bankrupt, which the Trustee or the Court can use their discretion to determine the ultimate payment to accrue to the estate. Section 68, as a complete code, allows for these issues to be taken into account.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">V. Remaining Areas of Disagreement</TI>
<P>54. The two remaining areas of disagreement between AAIRP and the Amicus are (a) the relevance of the &ldquo;pain and suffering cases&rdquo; and (b) the application of provincial wage exemptions.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>Relevance of &ldquo;Pain and Suffering&rdquo; Cases</UNDER></TI>
<P>55. The &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo; cases put forward by the Amicus closely align with the &ldquo;equitable approach&rdquo; used in the <EM>Neufeld</EM> decision and it was in <EM>Neufeld</EM> where an analogy was drawn to damages for pain and suffering. Other than in <EM>Neufeld</EM>, which has been criticized by other DTC income tax refund cases, &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo; cases have not factored into decisions regarding DTC income tax refunds.</P>
<P>56. As such, I submit that the &ldquo;pain and suffering&rdquo; cases are not applicable to the determination of this matter.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>V.</N><TI><UNDER>Why Provincial Wage Exemptions Do Not Apply</UNDER></TI>
<P>57. Provincial wage exemptions do not apply for two reasons: (a) section 68 is a complete code in respect of a bankrupt's wages; and (b) income tax refunds, generally, are immune from provincial garnishee summons.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI>Section 68 is a Complete Code for a Bankrupt's Wages</TI>
<P>58. In rendering its decision in <EM>Marzetti</EM>, Justice lacobucci for the SCC held that,
<QUOTE><P>...the language of s. 68, the inferred purpose of that provision, and the decision of this Court in <EM>Vachon</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, all support the conclusion that s. 68 is a substantive provision, one which is intended to operate as a complete code in respect of a bankrupt's salary, wages, or other remuneration.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Marzetti</EM>, at para. 67 at Part 2, Tab 1 of the Amicus' Brief.</P1></P>
<P>59. One of the reasons why the SCC reached this conclusion was because otherwise, the treatment of the bankrupt's wages would depend on their province of residence.
<QUOTE><P>Parliament no doubt considered it unreasonable for the treatment of bankrupt persons to depend upon the happenstance of provincial residence. Of course, even if one accepts that s. 68 is a complete code in respect of salary, wages, and other remuneration, the potential for uneven treatment across Canada remains in respect of other provincially exempted property. But it is hardly surprising that Parliament selected an important form of property&mdash;salary, wages and other remuneration&mdash;and gave that property special treatment.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Marzetti</EM>, at para. 63 at Part 2, Tab 1 of the Amicus' Brief.</P1></P>
<P>60. In support of the Court's reasoning in <EM>Marzetti</EM>, section 68 has been amended to even greater strengthen the argument that it is a complete code and align with the SCC's interpretation in <EM>Marzetti</EM>.
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(2)</N><TI>Definitions</TI><SSECP><DEF><DEFP><TERM>&ldquo;total income&rdquo;</TERM>
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>Includes,..., a bankrupt's <EM>revenues of whatever nature or from whatever source</EM> that are <UNDER>earned or received</UNDER> by the bankrupt between the date of the bankruptcy and the date of the bankrupt's discharge,...</PARAP></PARA></DEFP></DEF></SSECP></SSEC>
<P>(my emphasis)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>61. Under section 68, Trustees are required to collect a prescribed portion of the bankrupt's surplus income for the benefit of the debtor's estate and the benefit of creditors. Trustees calculate the amount of surplus income that a debtor may have with reference to the Superintendent of Bankrupt's standards, <EM>taking into account the personal and family situation of the bankrupt</EM>.</P>
<P>62. For our purposes, s. 68 being a complete code makes provincial wage exemptions inapplicable on one hand and gives discretion to the Trustee (or Court via application) on the other hand to take into account the bankrupt's personal and family situation. What is left is the bankrupt's personal and family situation still being addressed but instead of by provincial wage exemptions, it is by a discretionary application of the surplus income calculations.</P>
<P>63. Courts have used their discretion provided by s. 68(10) to declare that retroactive child support payments<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Re Dumont</SOC><CITE>2013 ABQB 692</CITE></CASEREF>;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, lump sum payments for past loss of income<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Re Anderson</SOC><CITE>2004 ABQB 349</CITE></CASEREF>;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and employment benefits<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Re Ferrara</SOC><CITE>2005 ABQB 61</CITE></CASEREF>;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> among others, not be included in the calculations of surplus income.
<P1><EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM>, s. 68(10); <BOLD>TAB 4</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Re Dumont</SOC><CITE>2013 ABQB 692 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>29</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <BOLD>TAB 5</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Re Anderson</SOC><CITE>2004 ABQB 349 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>27-28</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <BOLD>TAB 6</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Re Ferrara</SOC><CITE>2005 ABQB 61 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>3</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <BOLD>TAB 7</BOLD>.</P1></P>
<P>64. It is similarly open to this Court to declare that any DTC income tax refunds that would otherwise be payable to the Trustee as surplus income be excluded in the calculations of Ms. Chomistek's surplus income.</P>
<P>65. This discretion is important because it provides consistency across the country and eliminates the application of a provincial wage exemption from applying that could lead to a unwanted result, like income tax refunds arising from a debtor's &ldquo;RRSP stuffing&rdquo; prior to bankruptcy (but otherwise not voidable).</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Federal Crown's Immunity</TI>
<P>66. At common law, the Federal Crown is immune from garnishment. This principle is based on the Crown prerogative, which among other things, stands for the proposition that in the absence of a Federal statute enabling it, no order or injunction may be made against the Federal Crown.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>A. N.R. v. Croteau</SOC><CITE>1925 CanLII 46</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <BOLD>TAB 8</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Royal Bank of Canada v. Scott</SOC><CITE>1971 CanLII 1129</CITE><COURTJUR>NWTTC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <BOLD>TAB 9</BOLD>.</P1></P>
<P>67. This common law principle was codified by s.67 of the <EM>Financial Administration Act</EM> and s. 22 of the <EM>Crown Liability and Proceedings Act</EM>.
<P1><EM>Financial Administration Act</EM>, RSC 1985, c F-11, s. 67, <BOLD>TAB 10</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1><EM>Crown Liability and Proceedings Act</EM>, RSC 1985, c C-50, s. 22, <BOLD>TAB 10</BOLD>.</P1></P>
<P>68. Parliament is the only body who can legislate the Federal Crown out of the common law immunity, and it has done so in two respects: salaries of its employees and garnishment for family support orders&mdash;neither one is applicable in this case.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Garnishment, Attachment and Pension Diversion Act</EM>, R.S. 1985, c. G-2 and <EM>Family Orders and Enforcement Assistance Act</EM>, R.S. 1985, c.4 (2<SUP>nd</SUP> Supp.) and the <EM>Family Support Orders and Agreements G Regulations</EM>, SOR 88-181 and SOR 2006-296.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>69. The <EM>Civil Enforcement Act</EM> defines garnishees as &ldquo;persons&rdquo; and defines &ldquo;persons&rdquo; to include the &ldquo;Crown <UNDER>except where the context otherwise requires</UNDER>&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Civil Enforcement Act</EM>, RSA 2000, c.C-15, s.77(3) and s.1(ii), <BOLD>TAB 11</BOLD>.</P1></P>
<P>70. It is a long-standing constitutional principle that provincial legislatures cannot bind the Federal Crown. Given the crown prerogative and constitutional limitations of the Provincial legislature, I submit that the &ldquo;except where the context otherwise requires&rdquo; found in the definition of persons applies such that reference to the &ldquo;Crown&rdquo; only applies to the Province of Alberta, not the Federal Crown.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">VI. Conclusion</TI>
<P>71. The BIA is clear that income tax refunds for the year of the bankruptcy vest in the Trustee. We are then left with determining the treatment of the bankrupt's DTC income tax refunds that relate to the pre-bankruptcy tax years.</P>
<P>72. As identified by lacobucci J. and Major J.A. in their respective courts in <EM>Marzetti</EM>, the starting point is the character of the income tax refund itself. In this case, Ms. Chomistek's income tax refunds arose from wages.</P>
<P>73. Section 68 of the BIA provides a complete code with respect to a bankrupt's wages. Other than the refund amount attributable to the tax year of the bankruptcy, a lump sum pre-bankruptcy tax refund is really no different than a lump sum payment for pre-bankruptcy lost wages.</P>
<P>74. Section 68 requires a Trustee or Court to give regards to the <EM>personal and family situation</EM> of the bankrupt. Provincial wage exemptions do not apply and cases pertaining to pain and suffering are not relevant. The Trustee and the Court have discretion to determine the ultimate payment to accrue to the estate.</P>
